{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784873104406", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-87bb93e05680f201", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "cd /tmp && python3 -c \"\nfrom html.parser import HTMLParser\nimport re\n\nclass TextExtractor(HTMLParser):\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.text = []\n        self.skip = False\n        self.skip_tags = {'script', 'style', 'nav', 'header', 'footer'}\n    def handle_starttag(self, tag, attrs):\n        if tag in self.skip_tags:\n            self.skip = True\n    def handle_endtag(self, tag):\n        if tag in self.skip_tags:\n            self.skip = False\n    def handle_data(self, data):\n        if not self.skip:\n            d = data.strip()\n            if d:\n                self.text.append(d)\n\nwith open('2607.21127v1.html', 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    html = f.read()\n\nparser = TextExtractor()\nparser.feed(html)\ntext = '\\n'.join(parser.text)\n# Print full text\nprint(text[:80000])\n\" 2>&1 | head -3000", "description": "Extract full text from HTML", "timeout": 30000}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a319e1b7-9b31-44c3-8de5-779e67f5027e", "uuid": "68a7c11d-6644-48bb-ba11-b0dbe63e85b4"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-87bb93e05680f201", "type": "tool_result", "content": "<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (53.6KB). Full output saved to: /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/a319e1b7-9b31-44c3-8de5-779e67f5027e/tool-results/b54wc8o39.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\nToward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\nTitle:\nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\nDescription:\narXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\nLearn more\n×\nLicense: CC BY 4.0\narXiv:2607.21127v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026\nToward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\nViola Negroni\nviola.negroni@polimi.it\n0009-0000-2483-4366\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n,\nXin Wang\nwangxin@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\n,\nWanying Ge\ngewanying@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\n,\nPaolo Bestagini\npaolo.bestagini@polimi.it\n0000-0003-0406-0222\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n,\nJunichi Yamagishi\njyamagis@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\nand\nStefano Tubaro\nstefano.tubaro@polimi.it\n0000-0002-1990-9869\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n(2026)\nAbstract.\nIn this work, we propose an interpretable framework for speech deepfake detection based on artifact-specific expert models.\nRather than relying on black-box decisions, the framework provides human-understandable evidence, which is critical in high-stakes settings.\nEach expert is trained to detect a specific speech synthesis artifact, and its output is calibrated into a log-likelihood ratio that serves as an interpretable evidence score.\nWe evaluate five artifact-specific experts and show that, with proper calibration, they can capture their target artifacts and produce meaningful evidence.\nImportantly, each expert estimates only the presence of its assigned artifact rather than directly performing the final decision.\nTheir outputs are aggregated into an ensemble to produce the actual real-versus-fake classification, while maintaining interpretability by indicating how strongly each expert supports or contradicts a fake classification.\n...\n</persisted-output>\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a319e1b7-9b31-44c3-8de5-779e67f5027e", "uuid": "1dc156e6-524d-4bf7-b257-43adfdc3908c", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:05:09.756Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "Toward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\nTitle:\nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\nDescription:\narXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\nLearn more\n×\nLicense: CC BY 4.0\narXiv:2607.21127v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026\nToward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\nViola Negroni\nviola.negroni@polimi.it\n0009-0000-2483-4366\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n,\nXin Wang\nwangxin@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\n,\nWanying Ge\ngewanying@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\n,\nPaolo Bestagini\npaolo.bestagini@polimi.it\n0000-0003-0406-0222\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n,\nJunichi Yamagishi\njyamagis@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\nand\nStefano Tubaro\nstefano.tubaro@polimi.it\n0000-0002-1990-9869\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n(2026)\nAbstract.\nIn this work, we propose an interpretable framework for speech deepfake detection based on artifact-specific expert models.\nRather than relying on black-box decisions, the framework provides human-understandable evidence, which is critical in high-stakes settings.\nEach expert is trained to detect a specific speech synthesis artifact, and its output is calibrated into a log-likelihood ratio that serves as an interpretable evidence score.\nWe evaluate five artifact-specific experts and show that, with proper calibration, they can capture their target artifacts and produce meaningful evidence.\nImportantly, each expert estimates only the presence of its assigned artifact rather than directly performing the final decision.\nTheir outputs are aggregated into an ensemble to produce the actual real-versus-fake classification, while maintaining interpretability by indicating how strongly each expert supports or contradicts a fake classification.\nResults show that artifact-specific experts capture interpretable signals of synthetic speech across multiple generation pipelines.\nSpeech Deepfake Detection, Interpretability, Synthesis Artifacts, Text-to-speech, Audio Forensics\n†\n†\ncopyright:\nacmlicensed\n†\n†\njournalyear:\n2026\n†\n†\ndoi:\nXXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n†\n†\nccs:\nSecurity and privacy Spoofing attacks\n†\n†\nccs:\nSecurity and privacy Biometrics\n†\n†\nccs:\nApplied computing Computer forensics\n1.\nIntroduction\nSpeech deepfake detection aims to identify synthetic speech used for malicious purposes, such as impersonation, fraud, and misinformation.\nOver recent years, substantial progress has been achieved in detection performance\n(Jung\net al.\n,\n2022\n; Huang\net al.\n,\n2025\n; Xiao and Das,\n2025\n)\n. This progress has coincided with a shift from simpler machine learning approaches to increasingly complex\nDeep Learning (DL)\n-based systems, ranging from supervised models\n(Tak\net al.\n,\n2021\n; Jung\net al.\n,\n2022\n)\nto large pre-trained models\n(Wang and Yamagishi,\n2022\n; Ge\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\nand, more recently, large language model-based methods\n(Gu\net al.\n,\n2025\n; Xie\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\n.\nIn parallel, manually designed features\n(Borrelli\net al.\n,\n2021\n; Todisco\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\nhave progressively been replaced by learned self-supervised representations\n(Salvi\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\n.\nWhile these developments have improved performance, they have also reduced interpretability compared to classical approaches (e.g., decision trees and phonetic features\n(Machado\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n).\nIn high-stakes applications such as deepfake detection, where decisions may carry forensic, legal, or societal consequences, this lack of transparency becomes particularly problematic.\nSome post-hoc methods have been proposed to explain the behavior of black-box detectors\n(Ge\net al.\n,\n2022\n)\n.\nHowever, relying on post-hoc explanations for black-box models is fundamentally limited\n(Rudin,\n2019\n)\n, since these explanations do not guarantee faithful correspondence with the actual reasoning process of the classifier.\nInstead, interpretability should be embedded directly into the model design, so that the explanation itself corresponds to the mechanism used to reach the decision.\nRecent work has explored related directions.\nOne approach\n(Mishra\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\naugments real/fake detectors with auxiliary classifiers predicting attributes of the synthesis process, such as TTS vs. voice conversion and the generator’s DNN type. Another\n(Negroni\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\nadds branches predicting acoustic features and per-frame weights.\nWhile these methods provide additional signals, the resulting explanations remain coarse and do not directly expose nor quantify the evidence driving individual detection decisions.\nOur proposed framework explicitly targets intrinsically interpretable detection.\nAs shown in\nFigure\n1\n, the task is decomposed into predefined\nsynthesis artifacts\n, each handled by a dedicated expert model.\nExpert outputs are calibrated into interpretable\nLog-Likelihood Ratios (LLRs)\n, quantifying evidence for the presence of each artifact, and then aggregated into a global score.\nTo the best of our knowledge, this is the first work to frame speech deepfake detection as explicit artifact identification followed by\nLLR\n-based aggregation.\nConventional\nDL\n-based models implicitly learn artifacts without defining or isolating them, making it unclear whether decisions rely on meaningful cues or spurious correlations\n(Sahidullah\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n.\nThis raises concerns about their reliability.\nIn contrast, our approach is expected to mitigate the issue by replacing implicit artifact learning with an explicit formulation, where predefined synthesis artifacts are detected individually, and their evidence is combined via a principled\nLLR\n-based framework.\nRelatedly, the\nBinary-attribute-based-LR (BA-LR)\nframework for speaker verification\n(Ben-Amor\net al.\n,\n2023\n)\nalso produces attribute-specific LLRs, but it decomposes scores from a pretrained verifier using a surrogate model.\nThis top-down approach differs from ours, which directly computes and aggregates individual\nLLRs\nin a bottom-up manner.\nAs this is a preliminary, exploratory study, we focus on a set of artifacts well understood in the speech synthesis field.\nExperimental results show that the proposed method achieves meaningful detection performance while enabling the contribution of each expert to the final decision to be directly quantified and interpreted in terms of the presence of each artifact.\nAdditionally, the framework is modular by design, and new experts can be directly incorporated.\nThis additive design is well-suited to real-world deployment and may also facilitate the identification of dataset shortcuts and spurious correlations (see §\n5.5\n).\nFigure 1\n.\nOverview of the proposed framework for interpretable speech deepfake detection.\n2.\nProposed Method\nIn this section, we describe the proposed interpretable speech deepfake detection framework (detailed representation in\nFigure\n2\n) in the order of the problem formulation (§\n2.1\n), the design of artifact-specific expert models (§\n2.2\n), their calibration into\nLLRs\n(§\n2.3\n), and the aggregation of\nLLRs\n(§\n2.4\n).\n2.1.\nProblem Formulation\nGiven a discrete speech signal\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\nwith class label\ny\n∈\n{\n0\n,\n1\n}\ny\\in\\{0,1\\}\n, we consider two hypotheses:\nH\n0\nH_{0}\ndenotes the real class (\ny\n=\n0\ny=0\n) where\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\nis free of artifacts; and\nH\n1\nH_{1}\ndenotes the fake class (\ny\n=\n1\ny=1\n) where\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\ncontains synthesis artifacts.\nThe task is to determine the class of\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\nusing multiple artifact-specific experts.\nEach expert\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\ntargets a particular synthesis artifact and uses\nℱ\ni\n\\mathcal{F}_{i}\nto extract features relevant to the detection of the artifact. The raw output score of each expert\ns\ni\n≜\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\ns_{i}\\triangleq\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))\nis then calibrated towards a\nLLR\nusing a calibration function\n𝒞\n\\mathcal{C}\n, which can be written as\n(1)\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n≈\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n0\n)\n.\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{0})}.\nAn ideal LLR quantifies the evidence in favor of artifact presence, which is the foundation for ensembling multiple experts.\nAn ensemble with\nI\nI\nexperts can produce a system-level LLR\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\nby\n(2)\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\n𝐱\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\n𝐱\n|\nH\n0\n)\n\\displaystyle\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathbf{x}|H_{1})}{p(\\mathbf{x}|H_{0})}\n≈\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\n{\nℱ\n1\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n⋯\n,\nℱ\nI\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\n{\nℱ\n1\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n⋯\n,\nℱ\nI\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n|\nH\n0\n)\n\\displaystyle\\approx\\log\\frac{p(\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}|H_{1})}{p(\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}|H_{0})}\n(3)\n≈\n∑\ni\n=\n1\nI\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n0\n)\n.\n\\displaystyle\\approx\\sum_{i=1}^{I}\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{0})}.\nThe first approximation (Eq. (\n2\n)) assumes that the set of artifacts\n{\nℱ\n1\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n⋯\n,\nℱ\nI\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}\nsummarizes all the necessary artifacts to make the decision. The second approximation (Eq. (\n3\n)) assumes independence of the feature distributions given the hypothesis (\nH\n0\nH_{0}\nor\nH\n1\nH_{1}\n), which is known as the\nindependent additivity\nof individual LLRs\n(Jaynes,\n2003\n)\nand is widely used in multi-factor biometric authentication\n(Alonso-Fernandez\net al.\n,\n2022\n; Bassit\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\n1\n1\n1\nThe above formulation also differ from\nBA-LR\n(Ben-Amor\net al.\n,\n2023\n)\n, which solves the problem of decomposing\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\ninto\n{\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n0\n)\n}\ni\n=\n1\nI\n\\{\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{0})}\\}_{i=1}^{I}\nand learning the mapping from each\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\nto a specific speaker attribute.\nIn the context of deepfake detection, if each expert focuses on a different artifact and captures a different aspect of the signal,\nthe independent additivity of LLRs is a practical approximation.\nGiven\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\n, the ensemble system can decide\nH\n0\nH_{0}\nand\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nby comparing it with a pre-defined threshold following the Bayes decision theory.\n2\n2\n2\nSetting the threshold based on priors is well discussed in other literature\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2007\n, Eq. (6))\n. The threshold used in this study is discussed in §\n4\nSeveral technical questions need to be addressed.\nFirst, we need to design the experts and their corresponding\n{\nℱ\ni\n}\n\\{\\mathcal{F}_{i}\\}\n. Second, we need to properly implement the calibration function\n𝒞\n\\mathcal{C}\nso that\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n≈\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n.\nFinally, since LLRs are assumed to be independent, we may try alternative ways to fuse the LLRs.\n2.2.\nExpert Model Design\nTaking advantage of the knowledge from the speech synthesis field, we design experts and their corresponding\n{\nℱ\ni\n}\n\\{\\mathcal{F}_{i}\\}\nfor a set of well-known artifacts.\nAn artifact might be regarded as\na systematic and detectable deviation from real speech\n, potentially arising at different stages of synthesis (e.g., acoustic modeling or waveform generation).\nFor each type of artifact, we construct an expert\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nthat targets its detection.\nThe resulting set of experts forms the building block of our method, allowing decisions to be interpreted in terms of the presence or absence of specific artifacts in the given speech.\nHowever, it is not straightforward to learn the parameters of an artifact-specific\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nfrom fake data that is synthesized by existing speech generative models, because they may carry compounded artifacts.\nMoreover, training on real and fake samples offers limited control over the learned discriminative cues, and the model may end up relying on dataset-specific biases unrelated to the task\n(Sahidullah\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n.\nTo address this issue, we train each expert using a pseudo-fake generation strategy, in which the target artifact is simulated through a controlled manipulation applied to real speech.\nThis ensures that the simulated artifact is the only difference between real and pseudo-fake data, encouraging each expert to focus on the intended artifact.\nSpecifically, for a given artifact, we create manipulated speech from real utterances such that the applied manipulation emulates the target artifact while leaving other characteristics unchanged. To further enforce specialization, the input feature representation is deliberately designed to emphasize the artifact of interest and suppress unrelated information.\nFormally, for a given\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\n, we derive two training inputs for\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nusing the artifact-specific feature extraction\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\cdot)\nand manipulation\nℳ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{M}_{i}(\\cdot)\n:\n𝐳\n0\n=\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\mathbf{z}_{0}=\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\nand\n𝐳\n1\n=\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\nℳ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\n\\mathbf{z}_{1}=\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathcal{M}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))\n, with labels\ny\n=\n0\ny=0\nand\ny\n=\n1\ny=1\n, respectively. Each expert\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nis then trained as a binary classifier using multiple pairs of\n𝐳\n0\n\\mathbf{z}_{0}\nand\n𝐳\n1\n\\mathbf{z}_{1}\n.\nUsing pseudo-fake data not only facilitates the learning of artifact-specific experts but also simplifies data collection.\nThe set of artifacts investigated in this study is explained in §\n3\n.\nFigure 2\n.\nDetailed representation of the proposed framework (training and inference).\n2.3.\nModel Calibration\n2.3.1.\nMotivation\nAs mentioned in §\n2.1\n, we calibrate\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nfrom each expert so that its calibrated version better approximates\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n. In fact, using LLRs is not only preferred when fusing multiple experts (Eq. (\n3\n)) but also widely recognized by the forensic community as the proper way of representing “the value of the evidence\n…\n\\dots\nto be reported to a court of law”\n(Ramos\net al.\n,\n2017\n, § 14.3)\n.\nTo briefly explain the reasons, we note that making a Bayes decision given a single expert requires a comparison between the posterior odds\nlog\n⁡\nP\n​\n(\nH\n1\n|\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\nP\n​\n(\nH\n0\n|\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\n\\log\\frac{P(H_{1}|\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))}{P(H_{0}|\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))}\nagainst the decision cost ratio\nlog\n⁡\nC\n0\nC\n1\n\\log\\frac{C_{0}}{C_{1}}\n, where\nC\n0\nC_{0}\nand\nC\n1\nC_{1}\nare the costs for falsely classifying\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nand\nH\n0\nH_{0}\n, respectively.\nUsing Bayes’ rule, we get an equivalent decision strategy, which can be written as\n(4)\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n0\n)\n​\n≷\nH\n0\nH\n1\n​\nlog\n⁡\nC\n0\nC\n1\n+\nlog\n⁡\nP\n​\n(\nH\n0\n)\nP\n​\n(\nH\n1\n)\n,\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{0})}\\underset{H_{0}}{\\overset{H_{1}}{\\gtrless}}\\log\\frac{C_{0}}{C_{1}}+\\log\\frac{P(H_{0})}{P(H_{1})},\nwhere\nP\n​\n(\nH\n0\n)\nP(H_{0})\nand\nP\n​\n(\nH\n1\n)\nP(H_{1})\ndenote the class priors.\nThe main reason for producing and reporting LLRs is that they provide a\nuniversal interpretation\nof the strength of evidence in favor of a hypothesis\n(Ramos\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\n.\nThis interpretation is independent of the data prior probability, the backbone model, or input representation: for instance,\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\n0\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=0\ndoes not favor either one of the hypotheses, and\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\nlog\n⁡\n3\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=\\log 3\nmeans that “the evidence supports\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nagainst\nH\n0\nH_{0}\nwith a degree of 3 versus 1”.\n3\n3\n3\nAccording to the guideline of the European network of forensic science institutes\n(Champod\net al.\n,\n2016\n)\n, we may also verbally explain the support of evidence represented by the LLR.\nFor example,\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n>\nlog\n⁡\n10\n6\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})>\\log 10^{6}\ndenotes\nextremely strong\nsupport to\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nwhile\nlog\n⁡\n10\n4\n>\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n>\nlog\n⁡\n10\n3\n\\log 10^{4}>\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})>\\log 10^{3}\ndenotes\nmoderately strong\n.\nUniversal interpretation\nalso means that the LLRs of different experts are on the same scale and can be directly summed together (Eq. (\n3\n)).\nA further advantage, as shown in Eq. (\n4\n), is the separation between modeling and decision-making: the forensic examiner produces the LLR (left-hand side of Eq. (\n4\n)), while the decision threshold (right-hand side), based on priors and costs, is set by the court\n(Ramos\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\n.\nA binary classifier does not necessarily produce LLRs.\nFor instance, a probability-like\ns\ni\n∈\n[\n0\n,\n1\n]\ns_{i}\\in[0,1]\ncannot be interpreted as a log-likelihood ratio\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐳\n)\n∈\n(\n−\n∞\n,\n∞\n)\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{z})\\in(-\\infty,\\infty)\n.\nEven if transformed into an unbounded score, for example, using\nf\n​\n(\nx\n)\n=\nlog\n⁡\nx\n1\n−\nx\nf(x)=\\log\\frac{x}{1-x}\nfor\nx\n∈\n(\n0\n,\n1\n)\nx\\in(0,1)\n, the score still may not satisfy the statistical properties of true LLRs (e.g., “the LLR of the LLR is the LLR”\n(Mandasari,\n2018\n)\n).\n2.3.2.\nMethods\nThere are many possible ways of calibrating\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nso that\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n≈\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n.\nWe consider a generative approach\n(Brummer\net al.\n,\n2014\n)\n, which treats the expert outputs\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nas samples generated from class-conditional scores distributions\n{\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n;\nθ\n1\n)\n,\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n;\nθ\n0\n)\n}\n\\{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1}),\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})\\}\n: after estimating the two distributions, we calibrate by\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n=\nlog\n⁡\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n;\nθ\n1\n)\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n;\nθ\n0\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})=\\log\\frac{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1})}{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})}\n.\nIn practice, we need to choose the parametric form of such distributions.\nA fully flexible approach models each class distribution free-form, e.g., via\nKernel Density Estimation (KDE)\n(Cuccovillo\net al.\n,\n2023\n)\n.\nScores\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nare first mapped via Platt scaling (i.e., logistic regression\n1\n1\n+\nexp\n⁡\n(\na\n​\ns\ni\n+\nb\n)\n\\frac{1}{1+\\exp(as_{i}+b)}\nwith learned parameters\n{\na\n,\nb\n}\n\\{a,b\\}\n)\n(Platt,\n1999\n)\n, ensuring a bounded and monotonic score space suitable for density estimation.\nAfter that, class-conditional densities are then estimated using Gaussian\nKDE\n.\nWhile the\nKDE\n-based method is flexible, it provides no guarantee that\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\nis monotonic, which is often desirable for calibration.\nA more constrained form assumes that\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n;\nθ\n1\n)\n\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1})\nand\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n;\nθ\n0\n)\n\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})\nare Gaussian distributions with a tied standard deviation\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2013\n)\n, i.e.,\n(5)\np\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n)\n=\n𝒩\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nμ\nf\n,\nσ\n)\n,\np\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n)\n=\n𝒩\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nμ\nr\n,\nσ\n)\n,\np(s_{i}|H_{1})=\\mathcal{N}(s_{i}|\\mu_{f},\\sigma),\\quad p(s_{i}|H_{0})=\\mathcal{N}(s_{i}|\\mu_{r},\\sigma),\nwhere the learnable parameters are\nθ\n1\n=\n{\nμ\nf\n,\nσ\n}\n\\theta_{1}=\\{\\mu_{f},\\sigma\\}\nand\nθ\n0\n=\n{\nμ\nr\n,\nσ\n}\n\\theta_{0}=\\{\\mu_{r},\\sigma\\}\n.\nUnder this assumption, the resulting calibration reduces to an affine transformation\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n=\na\n​\ns\ni\n+\nb\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})=as_{i}+b\n, where\n(6)\na\n=\nμ\nf\n−\nμ\nr\nσ\n2\n,\nb\n=\n−\na\n​\n(\nμ\nf\n+\nμ\nr\n)\n2\n.\na=\\frac{\\mu_{\\text{f}}-\\mu_{\\text{r}}}{\\sigma^{2}},\\quad b=-\\frac{a(\\mu_{\\text{f}}+\\mu_{\\text{r}})}{2}.\nThis method is known as the constrained, maximum-likelihood, Gaussian (CMLG) calibration\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2013\n)\n.\nIn this work, we experiment with KDE and CMLG-based approaches.\nNote that each method requires a calibration set that is as representative as possible of the target (test) distribution, so that the estimated densities and resulting\nLLRs\nare meaningful.\nIf this set is not representative, the learned densities may be mismatched, leading to unreliable\nLLRs\n.\nThe choice of the calibration set is described in §\n4\n.\n2.4.\nEnsemble Aggregation Strategy\nOnce the\nLLRs\nare obtained, the straightforward approach is to sum them, motivated by the independent additivity of\nLLRs\n(Eq. (\n4\n)).\nWe also consider two alternative strategies.\nThe first uses a max operator\n(7)\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\nmax\ni\n⁡\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})=\\max_{i}\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),\nwhich retains only the strongest expert response for each sample and assumes that a single artifact may be sufficient for detection.\nThe second follows a Mixture-of-Experts formulation\n(Negroni\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\nand applies a learned gating mechanism\n(8)\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\n∑\ni\nw\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n​\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})=\\sum_{i}w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),\nwhere sample-dependent weights\nw\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n{w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})}\nadaptively combine expert\nLLRs\nby emphasizing the most relevant ones.\nIn practice, the calibrated per-expert scores are passed to a linear gating network with dimension equal to the number of experts, which outputs softmax-normalized weights\n{\nw\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n\\{w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\}\n.\nTable 1\n.\nFive artifacts investigated in this study. Abbreviations are defined for statistical parametric speech synthesis (SPSS) and line spectral frequency (LSF). Numbers in brackets for MLP-based expert architectures denote layer sizes.\nArtifact\nExample of target algorithm or module\nRaw features\nExpert input (#. proxy features)\nManipulation\nExpert Architecture\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ninconsistencies\nUnit selection\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ntrajectory\nvariability, 1st/2nd-order dynamics, ratios (10)\nshifting, shuffling, compression\nMLP (10–32–16–1)\nOversmoothed spectra\nAcoustic models in SPSS\nLSFs\nspatial/temporal spacing dynamics, coeff. variance (13)\ngaussian smoothing\nMLP (13–32–16–1)\nDegrade phase\nVocoders w/o modeling phase\nUnwrapped phase\n-\nminimum-phase reconstruction\nLight CNN (LCNN)\nEnergy inconsistencies\nUnit selection & SPSS\nLog-power spec.\nglobal + band energy, temporal deltas, drop stats (24)\nlocal attenuations\nMLP (24–32–16–1)\nTonal artifacts\nDNN-based vocoders\nSpectral fingerprint\n-\ninject resonances\nMLP (225–128–32–1)\nFigure 3\n.\nIllustrative real (top) vs. synthetic (bottom) examples for four\nof the targeted synthesis artifacts (left to right:\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ninconsistency, oversmoothing,\nenergy inconsistency, tonal artifact).\n3.\nArtifacts and Expert Models\nThis section outlines the artifacts and implementation of expert models for speech deepfake detection, designed based on our prior knowledge of speech synthesis algorithms.\nConsidering the variety of available approaches, we limit this preliminary work to\nText to Speech (TTS)\n, the most widely used and extensively studied speech synthesis paradigm, and its generated artifacts. Specifically, we consider\n5\n5\nmajor synthesis artifacts, spanning synthesis paradigms from unit selection to statistical parametric approaches, from linear models to neural methods; their implementation and association with specific deepfake families are detailed for each expert below (summary in\nTable\n1\n).\n3.1.\nF0 Inconsistencies\nGenerating an\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ntrajectory is essential for natural-sounding speech synthesis\n(Hirschberg,\n2002\n)\n. A known artifact in unit selection TTS is\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ninconsistency\n(Bořil\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\n, perceived as prosodic jumps or discontinuities in synthetic speech. This arises from the concatenation of segmented units.\nWe extract the\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ntrajectory using\npYIN\n(Mauch and Dixon,\n2014\n)\n, and apply manipulations within voiced regions. The contour is segmented into 80–160 ms units, and segments are randomly selected with probability\np\nseg\n∈\n[\n0.4\n,\n0.7\n]\np_{\\text{seg}}\\in[0.4,0.7]\n, scaled by factors in\n[\n0.87\n,\n0.92\n]\n[0.87,0.92]\nor\n[\n1.08\n,\n1.30\n]\n[1.08,1.30]\n. Selected segments are partially shuffled with probability\np\nshuffle\n∈\n[\n0.2\n,\n0.5\n]\np_{\\text{shuffle}}\\in[0.2,0.5]\n. Alternatively, with fixed probability, the\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ncontour is compressed toward its median (strength 0.4) and locally smoothed using a three-frame average (strength 0.4), reducing pitch variability. The procedure produces trajectories with either local discontinuities or reduced dynamics. Parameter ranges were empirically set to yield perceptually plausible yet pronounced artifacts for training.\nWe aggregate\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ncontours into scalar descriptors, forming a 10-dimensional feature vector for a\nMulti-Layer Perceptron (MLP)\nclassifier. Direct use of raw\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ncontours was ineffective.\n3.2.\nOversmoothing\nIn contrast to unit selection, statistical parametric speech synthesis (SPSS) uses statistical acoustic models to generate smoothed\nF\n0\nF_{0}\nand spectral trajectories\n(Tokuda\net al.\n,\n2013\n)\n.\nHowever, the generated features are often over-smoothed, resulting in muffled synthetic speech\n(Tokuda\net al.\n,\n2013\n)\n.\nThis was a central issue when using HMM\n(Tokuda\net al.\n,\n2013\n)\nand also affects more recent DNN-based acoustic models\n(Ren\net al.\n,\n2022\n)\n. The same issue can be caused by the DSP-based vocoders. Even if the trend is to switch to DNN-based vocoders, as long as the DNN-based vocoders are trained to minimize the distance of the spectral magnitude between generated and natural speech, the mean-seeking training paradigm is known to produce blurry (or over-smoothed) speech.\nWe simulate this effect by applying a Gaussian filter to\nLine Spectral Frequencies (LSF)\nalong the temporal axis, reducing frame-to-frame variation\n(Merritt and King,\n2013\n)\n.\nThe filter standard deviation is empirically set to\n2\n2\n.\nAfter filtering,\nLSF\ncoefficients are sorted within each frame to preserve ordering constraints. This yields trajectories with reduced temporal variability, approximating oversmoothed speech.\nRaw\nLSFs\nwere ineffective for training: we aggregate frame-level features over time into a 13-dimensional vector for\nMLP\n-based classification.\n3.3.\nDegraded Phase\nPhase artifacts commonly arise in three cases: 1) when using vocoders that assume a minimum-phase when reconstructing waveforms from spectral magnitude\n(Morise\net al.\n,\n2016\n)\n, 2) when using (typically DNN-based) vocoders that do not explicitly generate the phase\n(Kong\net al.\n,\n2020\n)\n, and 3) when the DNN cannot accurately generate the phase\n(Siuzdak,\n2024\n)\n.\nWe model this via controlled lossy phase reconstruction. The waveform is converted to the\nShort-Time Fourier Transform (STFT)\ndomain, retaining magnitude while discarding phase. A minimum-phase signal is reconstructed using cepstral processing by enforcing a causal liftering constraint on the log-magnitude spectrum, followed by inverse\nSTFT\n. From the reconstructed waveform, the unwrapped phase representation is extracted and used as input to a Light CNN model\n(Wu\net al.\n,\n2018\n)\n.\n3.4.\nEnergy Inconsistencies\nThis artifact occurs in both unit selection and SPSS-based TTS systems. In unit selection, it may result from imperfect concatenation, while in SPSS it appears as overly uniform regions or abrupt transitions, including unnaturally clean silences.\nWe simulate this by selecting a short temporal region (\n6\n6\n–\n30\n30\nframes) and attenuating it by a factor drawn from\n[\n0.0\n,\n0.5\n]\n[0.0,\\sqrt{0.5}]\n, producing local energy drops. The waveform is then converted to a power spectrogram via\nSTFT\nand log-scaled. We aggregate it into\n24\n24\nscalar descriptors capturing energy statistics and temporal drops, which are input to a\nMLP\n.\n3.5.\nTonal Artifacts\nNarrowband tonal artifacts can occur in neural\nTTS\nsystems using DNN-based upsampling modules, such as transposed or subpixel convolutions\n(Pons\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nThese may introduce spectral replicas and uneven overlap, producing spurious narrowband artifacts unrelated to natural harmonics. These are referred to as tonal artifacts\n(Pons\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nWe simulate this by attenuating the waveform by\n0.05\n0.05\n, then adding\n1\n1\n–\n2\n2\nnarrowband resonances using high-Q band-pass filters (1–8 kHz,\nQ\n∈\n[\n30\n,\n80\n]\nQ\\in[30,80]\n, gains\n[\n2\n,\n5\n]\n[2,5]\n).\nA nonlinearity increases contrast, followed by normalization, yielding signals dominated by sparse spectral peaks. A spectral fingerprint is extracted following\n(Afchar\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n, producing a 1D feature emphasizing these peaks for a\nMLP\n.\nFigure\n3\nshows representative real-vs-synthetic examples for four artifacts, illustrating the features used by the corresponding experts; the degraded phase is omitted due to limited suitability for 2D visualization.\nThe five artifacts are assumed to cover many speech synthesis systems in publicly available deepfake datasets\n(Wang\net al.\n,\n2020\n; Jung\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\n.\nMany voice conversion (VC) systems relying on statistical models and vocoders, DNN-based or not, may exhibit similar artifacts. A limitation of this approach is that only artifacts known a priori can be modeled by an expert. This is further discussed in §\n6\n.\n4.\nExperimental Setup\nThis section outlines the data splits (§\n4.1\n), training protocol (§\n4.2\n), and evaluation metrics (§\n4.3\n) used in our experiments.\n4.1.\nDatasets and Partitioning Protocol\nOur training data consists entirely of real speech drawn from the training sets of ASVspoof 2019\n(Wang\net al.\n,\n2020\n)\n(clean studio recordings), ASVspoof 5\n(Wang\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\n(controlled recordings), and SpoofCeleb\n(Jung\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\n(in-the-wild speech). We trim their leading and trailing silence and apply peak normalization to avoid potential shortcut learning during training\n(Müller\net al.\n,", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/a319e1b7-9b31-44c3-8de5-779e67f5027e/tool-results/b54wc8o39.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 54909}}
