{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-83ed1b28c927412e", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tToward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\n2\tTitle:\n3\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n4\tDescription:\n5\tarXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n6\tLearn more\n7\t×\n8\tLicense: CC BY 4.0\n9\tarXiv:2607.21127v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026\n10\tToward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\n11\tViola Negroni\n12\tviola.negroni@polimi.it\n13\t0009-0000-2483-4366\n14\tDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\n15\tMilano\n16\tItaly\n17\t,\n18\tXin Wang\n19\twangxin@nii.ac.jp\n20\tNational Institute of Informatics\n21\tTokyo\n22\tJapan\n23\t,\n24\tWanying Ge\n25\tgewanying@nii.ac.jp\n26\tNational Institute of Informatics\n27\tTokyo\n28\tJapan\n29\t,\n30\tPaolo Bestagini\n31\tpaolo.bestagini@polimi.it\n32\t0000-0003-0406-0222\n33\tDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\n34\tMilano\n35\tItaly\n36\t,\n37\tJunichi Yamagishi\n38\tjyamagis@nii.ac.jp\n39\tNational Institute of Informatics\n40\tTokyo\n41\tJapan\n42\tand\n43\tStefano Tubaro\n44\tstefano.tubaro@polimi.it\n45\t0000-0002-1990-9869\n46\tDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\n47\tMilano\n48\tItaly\n49\t(2026)\n50\tAbstract.\n51\tIn this work, we propose an interpretable framework for speech deepfake detection based on artifact-specific expert models.\n52\tRather than relying on black-box decisions, the framework provides human-understandable evidence, which is critical in high-stakes settings.\n53\tEach expert is trained to detect a specific speech synthesis artifact, and its output is calibrated into a log-likelihood ratio that serves as an interpretable evidence score.\n54\tWe evaluate five artifact-specific experts and show that, with proper calibration, they can capture their target artifacts and produce meaningful evidence.\n55\tImportantly, each expert estimates only the presence of its assigned artifact rather than directly performing the final decision.\n56\tTheir outputs are aggregated into an ensemble to produce the actual real-versus-fake classification, while maintaining interpretability by indicating how strongly each expert supports or contradicts a fake classification.\n57\tResults show that artifact-specific experts capture interpretable signals of synthetic speech across multiple generation pipelines.\n58\tSpeech Deepfake Detection, Interpretability, Synthesis Artifacts, Text-to-speech, Audio Forensics\n59\t†\n60\t†\n61\tcopyright:\n62\tacmlicensed\n63\t†\n64\t†\n65\tjournalyear:\n66\t2026\n67\t†\n68\t†\n69\tdoi:\n70\tXXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n71\t†\n72\t†\n73\tccs:\n74\tSecurity and privacy Spoofing attacks\n75\t†\n76\t†\n77\tccs:\n78\tSecurity and privacy Biometrics\n79\t†\n80\t†\n81\tccs:\n82\tApplied computing Computer forensics\n83\t1.\n84\tIntroduction\n85\tSpeech deepfake detection aims to identify synthetic speech used for malicious purposes, such as impersonation, fraud, and misinformation.\n86\tOver recent years, substantial progress has been achieved in detection performance\n87\t(Jung\n88\tet al.\n89\t,\n90\t2022\n91\t; Huang\n92\tet al.\n93\t,\n94\t2025\n95\t; Xiao and Das,\n96\t2025\n97\t)\n98\t. This progress has coincided with a shift from simpler machine learning approaches to increasingly complex\n99\tDeep Learning (DL)\n100\t-based systems, ranging from supervised models\n101\t(Tak\n102\tet al.\n103\t,\n104\t2021\n105\t; Jung\n106\tet al.\n107\t,\n108\t2022\n109\t)\n110\tto large pre-trained models\n111\t(Wang and Yamagishi,\n112\t2022\n113\t; Ge\n114\tet al.\n115\t,\n116\t2025\n117\t)\n118\tand, more recently, large language model-based methods\n119\t(Gu\n120\tet al.\n121\t,\n122\t2025\n123\t; Xie\n124\tet al.\n125\t,\n126\t2026\n127\t)\n128\t.\n129\tIn parallel, manually designed features\n130\t(Borrelli\n131\tet al.\n132\t,\n133\t2021\n134\t; Todisco\n135\tet al.\n136\t,\n137\t2017\n138\t)\n139\thave progressively been replaced by learned self-supervised representations\n140\t(Salvi\n141\tet al.\n142\t,\n143\t2024\n144\t)\n145\t.\n146\tWhile these developments have improved performance, they have also reduced interpretability compared to classical approaches (e.g., decision trees and phonetic features\n147\t(Machado\n148\tet al.\n149\t,\n150\t2025\n151\t)\n152\t).\n153\tIn high-stakes applications such as deepfake detection, where decisions may carry forensic, legal, or societal consequences, this lack of transparency becomes particularly problematic.\n154\tSome post-hoc methods have been proposed to explain the behavior of black-box detectors\n155\t(Ge\n156\tet al.\n157\t,\n158\t2022\n159\t)\n160\t.\n161\tHowever, relying on post-hoc explanations for black-box models is fundamentally limited\n162\t(Rudin,\n163\t2019\n164\t)\n165\t, since these explanations do not guarantee faithful correspondence with the actual reasoning process of the classifier.\n166\tInstead, interpretability should be embedded directly into the model design, so that the explanation itself corresponds to the mechanism used to reach the decision.\n167\tRecent work has explored related directions.\n168\tOne approach\n169\t(Mishra\n170\tet al.\n171\t,\n172\t2026\n173\t)\n174\taugments real/fake detectors with auxiliary classifiers predicting attributes of the synthesis process, such as TTS vs. voice conversion and the generator’s DNN type. Another\n175\t(Negroni\n176\tet al.\n177\t,\n178\t2026\n179\t)\n180\tadds branches predicting acoustic features and per-frame weights.\n181\tWhile these methods provide additional signals, the resulting explanations remain coarse and do not directly expose nor quantify the evidence driving individual detection decisions.\n182\tOur proposed framework explicitly targets intrinsically interpretable detection.\n183\tAs shown in\n184\tFigure\n185\t1\n186\t, the task is decomposed into predefined\n187\tsynthesis artifacts\n188\t, each handled by a dedicated expert model.\n189\tExpert outputs are calibrated into interpretable\n190\tLog-Likelihood Ratios (LLRs)\n191\t, quantifying evidence for the presence of each artifact, and then aggregated into a global score.\n192\tTo the best of our knowledge, this is the first work to frame speech deepfake detection as explicit artifact identification followed by\n193\tLLR\n194\t-based aggregation.\n195\tConventional\n196\tDL\n197\t-based models implicitly learn artifacts without defining or isolating them, making it unclear whether decisions rely on meaningful cues or spurious correlations\n198\t(Sahidullah\n199\tet al.\n200\t,\n201\t2025\n202\t)\n203\t.\n204\tThis raises concerns about their reliability.\n205\tIn contrast, our approach is expected to mitigate the issue by replacing implicit artifact learning with an explicit formulation, where predefined synthesis artifacts are detected individually, and their evidence is combined via a principled\n206\tLLR\n207\t-based framework.\n208\tRelatedly, the\n209\tBinary-attribute-based-LR (BA-LR)\n210\tframework for speaker verification\n211\t(Ben-Amor\n212\tet al.\n213\t,\n214\t2023\n215\t)\n216\talso produces attribute-specific LLRs, but it decomposes scores from a pretrained verifier using a surrogate model.\n217\tThis top-down approach differs from ours, which directly computes and aggregates individual\n218\tLLRs\n219\tin a bottom-up manner.\n220\tAs this is a preliminary, exploratory study, we focus on a set of artifacts well understood in the speech synthesis field.\n221\tExperimental results show that the proposed method achieves meaningful detection performance while enabling the contribution of each expert to the final decision to be directly quantified and interpreted in terms of the presence of each artifact.\n222\tAdditionally, the framework is modular by design, and new experts can be directly incorporated.\n223\tThis additive design is well-suited to real-world deployment and may also facilitate the identification of dataset shortcuts and spurious correlations (see §\n224\t5.5\n225\t).\n226\tFigure 1\n227\t.\n228\tOverview of the proposed framework for interpretable speech deepfake detection.\n229\t2.\n230\tProposed Method\n231\tIn this section, we describe the proposed interpretable speech deepfake detection framework (detailed representation in\n232\tFigure\n233\t2\n234\t) in the order of the problem formulation (§\n235\t2.1\n236\t), the design of artifact-specific expert models (§\n237\t2.2\n238\t), their calibration into\n239\tLLRs\n240\t(§\n241\t2.3\n242\t), and the aggregation of\n243\tLLRs\n244\t(§\n245\t2.4\n246\t).\n247\t2.1.\n248\tProblem Formulation\n249\tGiven a discrete speech signal\n250\t𝐱\n251\t\\mathbf{x}\n252\twith class label\n253\ty\n254\t∈\n255\t{\n256\t0\n257\t,\n258\t1\n259\t}\n260\ty\\in\\{0,1\\}\n261\t, we consider two hypotheses:\n262\tH\n263\t0\n264\tH_{0}\n265\tdenotes the real class (\n266\ty\n267\t=\n268\t0\n269\ty=0\n270\t) where\n271\t𝐱\n272\t\\mathbf{x}\n273\tis free of artifacts; and\n274\tH\n275\t1\n276\tH_{1}\n277\tdenotes the fake class (\n278\ty\n279\t=\n280\t1\n281\ty=1\n282\t) where\n283\t𝐱\n284\t\\mathbf{x}\n285\tcontains synthesis artifacts.\n286\tThe task is to determine the class of\n287\t𝐱\n288\t\\mathbf{x}\n289\tusing multiple artifact-specific experts.\n290\tEach expert\n291\tℰ\n292\ti\n293\t​\n294\t(\n295\t⋅\n296\t)\n297\t\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\n298\ttargets a particular synthesis artifact and uses\n299\tℱ\n300\ti\n301\t\\mathcal{F}_{i}\n302\tto extract features relevant to the detection of the artifact. The raw output score of each expert\n303\ts\n304\ti\n305\t≜\n306\tℰ\n307\ti\n308\t​\n309\t(\n310\tℱ\n311\ti\n312\t​\n313\t(\n314\t𝐱\n315\t)\n316\t)\n317\ts_{i}\\triangleq\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))\n318\tis then calibrated towards a\n319\tLLR\n320\tusing a calibration function\n321\t𝒞\n322\t\\mathcal{C}\n323\t, which can be written as\n324\t(1)\n325\t𝒞\n326\t​\n327\t(\n328\ts\n329\ti\n330\t)\n331\t≈\n332\tℓ\n333\ti\n334\t​\n335\t(\n336\t𝐱\n337\t)\n338\t≜\n339\tlog\n340\t⁡\n341\tp\n342\t​\n343\t(\n344\tℱ\n345\ti\n346\t​\n347\t(\n348\t𝐱\n349\t)\n350\t∣\n351\tH\n352\t1\n353\t)\n354\tp\n355\t​\n356\t(\n357\tℱ\n358\ti\n359\t​\n360\t(\n361\t𝐱\n362\t)\n363\t∣\n364\tH\n365\t0\n366\t)\n367\t.\n368\t\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{0})}.\n369\tAn ideal LLR quantifies the evidence in favor of artifact presence, which is the foundation for ensembling multiple experts.\n370\tAn ensemble with\n371\tI\n372\tI\n373\texperts can produce a system-level LLR\n374\tℓ\n375\t​\n376\t(\n377\t𝐱\n378\t)\n379\t\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\n380\tby\n381\t(2)\n382\tℓ\n383\t​\n384\t(\n385\t𝐱\n386\t)\n387\t≜\n388\tlog\n389\t⁡\n390\tp\n391\t​\n392\t(\n393\t𝐱\n394\t|\n395\tH\n396\t1\n397\t)\n398\tp\n399\t​\n400\t(\n401\t𝐱\n402\t|\n403\tH\n404\t0\n405\t)\n406\t\\displaystyle\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathbf{x}|H_{1})}{p(\\mathbf{x}|H_{0})}\n407\t≈\n408\tlog\n409\t⁡\n410\tp\n411\t​\n412\t(\n413\t{\n414\tℱ\n415\t1\n416\t​\n417\t(\n418\t𝐱\n419\t)\n420\t,\n421\t⋯\n422\t,\n423\tℱ\n424\tI\n425\t​\n426\t(\n427\t𝐱\n428\t)\n429\t}\n430\t|\n431\tH\n432\t1\n433\t)\n434\tp\n435\t​\n436\t(\n437\t{\n438\tℱ\n439\t1\n440\t​\n441\t(\n442\t𝐱\n443\t)\n444\t,\n445\t⋯\n446\t,\n447\tℱ\n448\tI\n449\t​\n450\t(\n451\t𝐱\n452\t)\n453\t}\n454\t|\n455\tH\n456\t0\n457\t)\n458\t\\displaystyle\\approx\\log\\frac{p(\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}|H_{1})}{p(\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}|H_{0})}\n459\t(3)\n460\t≈\n461\t∑\n462\ti\n463\t=\n464\t1\n465\tI\n466\tlog\n467\t⁡\n468\tp\n469\t​\n470\t(\n471\tℱ\n472\ti\n473\t​\n474\t(\n475\t𝐱\n476\t)\n477\t|\n478\tH\n479\t1\n480\t)\n481\tp\n482\t​\n483\t(\n484\tℱ\n485\ti\n486\t​\n487\t(\n488\t𝐱\n489\t)\n490\t|\n491\tH\n492\t0\n493\t)\n494\t.\n495\t\\displaystyle\\approx\\sum_{i=1}^{I}\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{0})}.\n496\tThe first approximation (Eq. (\n497\t2\n498\t)) assumes that the set of artifacts\n499\t{\n500\tℱ\n501\t1\n502\t​\n503\t(\n504\t𝐱\n505\t)\n506\t,\n507\t⋯\n508\t,\n509\tℱ\n510\tI\n511\t​\n512\t(\n513\t𝐱\n514\t)\n515\t}\n516\t\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}\n517\tsummarizes all the necessary artifacts to make the decision. The second approximation (Eq. (\n518\t3\n519\t)) assumes independence of the feature distributions given the hypothesis (\n520\tH\n521\t0\n522\tH_{0}\n523\tor\n524\tH\n525\t1\n526\tH_{1}\n527\t), which is known as the\n528\tindependent additivity\n529\tof individual LLRs\n530\t(Jaynes,\n531\t2003\n532\t)\n533\tand is widely used in multi-factor biometric authentication\n534\t(Alonso-Fernandez\n535\tet al.\n536\t,\n537\t2022\n538\t; Bassit\n539\tet al.\n540\t,\n541\t2021\n542\t)\n543\t.\n544\t1\n545\t1\n546\t1\n547\tThe above formulation also differ from\n548\tBA-LR\n549\t(Ben-Amor\n550\tet al.\n551\t,\n552\t2023\n553\t)\n554\t, which solves the problem of decomposing\n555\tℓ\n556\t​\n557\t(\n558\t𝐱\n559\t)\n560\t\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\n561\tinto\n562\t{\n563\tℓ\n564\ti\n565\t​\n566\t(\n567\t𝐱\n568\t)\n569\t≜\n570\tlog\n571\t⁡\n572\tp\n573\t​\n574\t(\n575\tℱ\n576\ti\n577\t​\n578\t(\n579\t𝐱\n580\t)\n581\t∣\n582\tH\n583\t1\n584\t)\n585\tp\n586\t​\n587\t(\n588\tℱ\n589\ti\n590\t​\n591\t(\n592\t𝐱\n593\t)\n594\t∣\n595\tH\n596\t0\n597\t)\n598\t}\n599\ti\n600\t=\n601\t1\n602\tI\n603\t\\{\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{0})}\\}_{i=1}^{I}\n604\tand learning the mapping from each\n605\tℓ\n606\ti\n607\t​\n608\t(\n609\t𝐱\n610\t)\n611\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n612\tto a specific speaker attribute.\n613\tIn the context of deepfake detection, if each expert focuses on a different artifact and captures a different aspect of the signal,\n614\tthe independent additivity of LLRs is a practical approximation.\n615\tGiven\n616\tℓ\n617\t​\n618\t(\n619\t𝐱\n620\t)\n621\t\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\n622\t, the ensemble system can decide\n623\tH\n624\t0\n625\tH_{0}\n626\tand\n627\tH\n628\t1\n629\tH_{1}\n630\tby comparing it with a pre-defined threshold following the Bayes decision theory.\n631\t2\n632\t2\n633\t2\n634\tSetting the threshold based on priors is well discussed in other literature\n635\t(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n636\t2007\n637\t, Eq. (6))\n638\t. The threshold used in this study is discussed in §\n639\t4\n640\tSeveral technical questions need to be addressed.\n641\tFirst, we need to design the experts and their corresponding\n642\t{\n643\tℱ\n644\ti\n645\t}\n646\t\\{\\mathcal{F}_{i}\\}\n647\t. Second, we need to properly implement the calibration function\n648\t𝒞\n649\t\\mathcal{C}\n650\tso that\n651\t𝒞\n652\t​\n653\t(\n654\ts\n655\ti\n656\t)\n657\t≈\n658\tℓ\n659\ti\n660\t​\n661\t(\n662\t𝐱\n663\t)\n664\t\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n665\t.\n666\tFinally, since LLRs are assumed to be independent, we may try alternative ways to fuse the LLRs.\n667\t2.2.\n668\tExpert Model Design\n669\tTaking advantage of the knowledge from the speech synthesis field, we design experts and their corresponding\n670\t{\n671\tℱ\n672\ti\n673\t}\n674\t\\{\\mathcal{F}_{i}\\}\n675\tfor a set of well-known artifacts.\n676\tAn artifact might be regarded as\n677\ta systematic and detectable deviation from real speech\n678\t, potentially arising at different stages of synthesis (e.g., acoustic modeling or waveform generation).\n679\tFor each type of artifact, we construct an expert\n680\tℰ\n681\ti\n682\t​\n683\t(\n684\t⋅\n685\t)\n686\t\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\n687\tthat targets its detection.\n688\tThe resulting set of experts forms the building block of our method, allowing decisions to be interpreted in terms of the presence or absence of specific artifacts in the given speech.\n689\tHowever, it is not straightforward to learn the parameters of an artifact-specific\n690\tℰ\n691\ti\n692\t​\n693\t(\n694\t⋅\n695\t)\n696\t\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\n697\tfrom fake data that is synthesized by existing speech generative models, because they may carry compounded artifacts.\n698\tMoreover, training on real and fake samples offers limited control over the learned discriminative cues, and the model may end up relying on dataset-specific biases unrelated to the task\n699\t(Sahidullah\n700\tet al.\n701\t,\n702\t2025\n703\t)\n704\t.\n705\tTo address this issue, we train each expert using a pseudo-fake generation strategy, in which the target artifact is simulated through a controlled manipulation applied to real speech.\n706\tThis ensures that the simulated artifact is the only difference between real and pseudo-fake data, encouraging each expert to focus on the intended artifact.\n707\tSpecifically, for a given artifact, we create manipulated speech from real utterances such that the applied manipulation emulates the target artifact while leaving other characteristics unchanged. To further enforce specialization, the input feature representation is deliberately designed to emphasize the artifact of interest and suppress unrelated information.\n708\tFormally, for a given\n709\t𝐱\n710\t\\mathbf{x}\n711\t, we derive two training inputs for\n712\tℰ\n713\ti\n714\t​\n715\t(\n716\t⋅\n717\t)\n718\t\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\n719\tusing the artifact-specific feature extraction\n720\tℱ\n721\ti\n722\t​\n723\t(\n724\t⋅\n725\t)\n726\t\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\cdot)\n727\tand manipulation\n728\tℳ\n729\ti\n730\t​\n731\t(\n732\t⋅\n733\t)\n734\t\\mathcal{M}_{i}(\\cdot)\n735\t:\n736\t𝐳\n737\t0\n738\t=\n739\tℱ\n740\ti\n741\t​\n742\t(\n743\t𝐱\n744\t)\n745\t\\mathbf{z}_{0}=\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n746\tand\n747\t𝐳\n748\t1\n749\t=\n750\tℱ\n751\ti\n752\t​\n753\t(\n754\tℳ\n755\ti\n756\t​\n757\t(\n758\t𝐱\n759\t)\n760\t)\n761\t\\mathbf{z}_{1}=\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathcal{M}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))\n762\t, with labels\n763\ty\n764\t=\n765\t0\n766\ty=0\n767\tand\n768\ty\n769\t=\n770\t1\n771\ty=1\n772\t, respectively. Each expert\n773\tℰ\n774\ti\n775\t​\n776\t(\n777\t⋅\n778\t)\n779\t\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\n780\tis then trained as a binary classifier using multiple pairs of\n781\t𝐳\n782\t0\n783\t\\mathbf{z}_{0}\n784\tand\n785\t𝐳\n786\t1\n787\t\\mathbf{z}_{1}\n788\t.\n789\tUsing pseudo-fake data not only facilitates the learning of artifact-specific experts but also simplifies data collection.\n790\tThe set of artifacts investigated in this study is explained in §\n791\t3\n792\t.\n793\tFigure 2\n794\t.\n795\tDetailed representation of the proposed framework (training and inference).\n796\t2.3.\n797\tModel Calibration\n798\t2.3.1.\n799\tMotivation\n800\tAs mentioned in §\n801\t2.1\n802\t, we calibrate\n803\ts\n804\ti\n805\ts_{i}\n806\tfrom each expert so that its calibrated version better approximates\n807\tℓ\n808\ti\n809\t​\n810\t(\n811\t𝐱\n812\t)\n813\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n814\t. In fact, using LLRs is not only preferred when fusing multiple experts (Eq. (\n815\t3\n816\t)) but also widely recognized by the forensic community as the proper way of representing “the value of the evidence\n817\t…\n818\t\\dots\n819\tto be reported to a court of law”\n820\t(Ramos\n821\tet al.\n822\t,\n823\t2017\n824\t, § 14.3)\n825\t.\n826\tTo briefly explain the reasons, we note that making a Bayes decision given a single expert requires a comparison between the posterior odds\n827\tlog\n828\t⁡\n829\tP\n830\t​\n831\t(\n832\tH\n833\t1\n834\t|\n835\tℱ\n836\ti\n837\t​\n838\t(\n839\t𝐱\n840\t)\n841\t)\n842\tP\n843\t​\n844\t(\n845\tH\n846\t0\n847\t|\n848\tℱ\n849\ti\n850\t​\n851\t(\n852\t𝐱\n853\t)\n854\t)\n855\t\\log\\frac{P(H_{1}|\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))}{P(H_{0}|\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))}\n856\tagainst the decision cost ratio\n857\tlog\n858\t⁡\n859\tC\n860\t0\n861\tC\n862\t1\n863\t\\log\\frac{C_{0}}{C_{1}}\n864\t, where\n865\tC\n866\t0\n867\tC_{0}\n868\tand\n869\tC\n870\t1\n871\tC_{1}\n872\tare the costs for falsely classifying\n873\tH\n874\t1\n875\tH_{1}\n876\tand\n877\tH\n878\t0\n879\tH_{0}\n880\t, respectively.\n881\tUsing Bayes’ rule, we get an equivalent decision strategy, which can be written as\n882\t(4)\n883\tℓ\n884\ti\n885\t​\n886\t(\n887\t𝐱\n888\t)\n889\t≜\n890\tlog\n891\t⁡\n892\tp\n893\t​\n894\t(\n895\tℱ\n896\ti\n897\t​\n898\t(\n899\t𝐱\n900\t)\n901\t|\n902\tH\n903\t1\n904\t)\n905\tp\n906\t​\n907\t(\n908\tℱ\n909\ti\n910\t​\n911\t(\n912\t𝐱\n913\t)\n914\t|\n915\tH\n916\t0\n917\t)\n918\t​\n919\t≷\n920\tH\n921\t0\n922\tH\n923\t1\n924\t​\n925\tlog\n926\t⁡\n927\tC\n928\t0\n929\tC\n930\t1\n931\t+\n932\tlog\n933\t⁡\n934\tP\n935\t​\n936\t(\n937\tH\n938\t0\n939\t)\n940\tP\n941\t​\n942\t(\n943\tH\n944\t1\n945\t)\n946\t,\n947\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{0})}\\underset{H_{0}}{\\overset{H_{1}}{\\gtrless}}\\log\\frac{C_{0}}{C_{1}}+\\log\\frac{P(H_{0})}{P(H_{1})},\n948\twhere\n949\tP\n950\t​\n951\t(\n952\tH\n953\t0\n954\t)\n955\tP(H_{0})\n956\tand\n957\tP\n958\t​\n959\t(\n960\tH\n961\t1\n962\t)\n963\tP(H_{1})\n964\tdenote the class priors.\n965\tThe main reason for producing and reporting LLRs is that they provide a\n966\tuniversal interpretation\n967\tof the strength of evidence in favor of a hypothesis\n968\t(Ramos\n969\tet al.\n970\t,\n971\t2017\n972\t)\n973\t.\n974\tThis interpretation is independent of the data prior probability, the backbone model, or input representation: for instance,\n975\tℓ\n976\ti\n977\t​\n978\t(\n979\t𝐱\n980\t)\n981\t=\n982\t0\n983\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=0\n984\tdoes not favor either one of the hypotheses, and\n985\tℓ\n986\ti\n987\t​\n988\t(\n989\t𝐱\n990\t)\n991\t=\n992\tlog\n993\t⁡\n994\t3\n995\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=\\log 3\n996\tmeans that “the evidence supports\n997\tH\n998\t1\n999\tH_{1}\n1000\tagainst\n1001\tH\n1002\t0\n1003\tH_{0}\n1004\twith a degree of 3 versus 1”.\n1005\t3\n1006\t3\n1007\t3\n1008\tAccording to the guideline of the European network of forensic science institutes\n1009\t(Champod\n1010\tet al.\n1011\t,\n1012\t2016\n1013\t)\n1014\t, we may also verbally explain the support of evidence represented by the LLR.\n1015\tFor example,\n1016\tℓ\n1017\ti\n1018\t​\n1019\t(\n1020\t𝐱\n1021\t)\n1022\t>\n1023\tlog\n1024\t⁡\n1025\t10\n1026\t6\n1027\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})>\\log 10^{6}\n1028\tdenotes\n1029\textremely strong\n1030\tsupport to\n1031\tH\n1032\t1\n1033\tH_{1}\n1034\twhile\n1035\tlog\n1036\t⁡\n1037\t10\n1038\t4\n1039\t>\n1040\tℓ\n1041\ti\n1042\t​\n1043\t(\n1044\t𝐱\n1045\t)\n1046\t>\n1047\tlog\n1048\t⁡\n1049\t10\n1050\t3\n1051\t\\log 10^{4}>\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})>\\log 10^{3}\n1052\tdenotes\n1053\tmoderately strong\n1054\t.\n1055\tUniversal interpretation\n1056\talso means that the LLRs of different experts are on the same scale and can be directly summed together (Eq. (\n1057\t3\n1058\t)).\n1059\tA further advantage, as shown in Eq. (\n1060\t4\n1061\t), is the separation between modeling and decision-making: the forensic examiner produces the LLR (left-hand side of Eq. (\n1062\t4\n1063\t)), while the decision threshold (right-hand side), based on priors and costs, is set by the court\n1064\t(Ramos\n1065\tet al.\n1066\t,\n1067\t2017\n1068\t)\n1069\t.\n1070\tA binary classifier does not necessarily produce LLRs.\n1071\tFor instance, a probability-like\n1072\ts\n1073\ti\n1074\t∈\n1075\t[\n1076\t0\n1077\t,\n1078\t1\n1079\t]\n1080\ts_{i}\\in[0,1]\n1081\tcannot be interpreted as a log-likelihood ratio\n1082\tℓ\n1083\ti\n1084\t​\n1085\t(\n1086\t𝐳\n1087\t)\n1088\t∈\n1089\t(\n1090\t−\n1091\t∞\n1092\t,\n1093\t∞\n1094\t)\n1095\t\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{z})\\in(-\\infty,\\infty)\n1096\t.\n1097\tEven if transformed into an unbounded score, for example, using\n1098\tf\n1099\t​\n1100\t(\n1101\tx\n1102\t)\n1103\t=\n1104\tlog\n1105\t⁡\n1106\tx\n1107\t1\n1108\t−\n1109\tx\n1110\tf(x)=\\log\\frac{x}{1-x}\n1111\tfor\n1112\tx\n1113\t∈\n1114\t(\n1115\t0\n1116\t,\n1117\t1\n1118\t)\n1119\tx\\in(0,1)\n1120\t, the score still may not satisfy the statistical properties of true LLRs (e.g., “the LLR of the LLR is the LLR”\n1121\t(Mandasari,\n1122\t2018\n1123\t)\n1124\t).\n1125\t2.3.2.\n1126\tMethods\n1127\tThere are many possible ways of calibrating\n1128\ts\n1129\ti\n1130\ts_{i}\n1131\tso that\n1132\t𝒞\n1133\t​\n1134\t(\n1135\ts\n1136\ti\n1137\t)\n1138\t≈\n1139\tℓ\n1140\ti\n1141\t​\n1142\t(\n1143\t𝐱\n1144\t)\n1145\t\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n1146\t.\n1147\tWe consider a generative approach\n1148\t(Brummer\n1149\tet al.\n1150\t,\n1151\t2014\n1152\t)\n1153\t, which treats the expert outputs\n1154\ts\n1155\ti\n1156\ts_{i}\n1157\tas samples generated from class-conditional scores distributions\n1158\t{\n1159\tp\n1160\t~\n1161\t​\n1162\t(\n1163\ts\n1164\ti\n1165\t|\n1166\tH\n1167\t1\n1168\t;\n1169\tθ\n1170\t1\n1171\t)\n1172\t,\n1173\tp\n1174\t~\n1175\t​\n1176\t(\n1177\ts\n1178\ti\n1179\t|\n1180\tH\n1181\t0\n1182\t;\n1183\tθ\n1184\t0\n1185\t)\n1186\t}\n1187\t\\{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1}),\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})\\}\n1188\t: after estimating the two distributions, we calibrate by\n1189\t𝒞\n1190\t​\n1191\t(\n1192\ts\n1193\ti\n1194\t)\n1195\t=\n1196\tlog\n1197\t⁡\n1198\tp\n1199\t~\n1200\t​\n1201\t(\n1202\ts\n1203\ti\n1204\t|\n1205\tH\n1206\t1\n1207\t;\n1208\tθ\n1209\t1\n1210\t)\n1211\tp\n1212\t~\n1213\t​\n1214\t(\n1215\ts\n1216\ti\n1217\t|\n1218\tH\n1219\t0\n1220\t;\n1221\tθ\n1222\t0\n1223\t)\n1224\t\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})=\\log\\frac{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1})}{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})}\n1225\t.\n1226\tIn practice, we need to choose the parametric form of such distributions.\n1227\tA fully flexible approach models each class distribution free-form, e.g., via\n1228\tKernel Density Estimation (KDE)\n1229\t(Cuccovillo\n1230\tet al.\n1231\t,\n1232\t2023\n1233\t)\n1234\t.\n1235\tScores\n1236\ts\n1237\ti\n1238\ts_{i}\n1239\tare first mapped via Platt scaling (i.e., logistic regression\n1240\t1\n1241\t1\n1242\t+\n1243\texp\n1244\t⁡\n1245\t(\n1246\ta\n1247\t​\n1248\ts\n1249\ti\n1250\t+\n1251\tb\n1252\t)\n1253\t\\frac{1}{1+\\exp(as_{i}+b)}\n1254\twith learned parameters\n1255\t{\n1256\ta\n1257\t,\n1258\tb\n1259\t}\n1260\t\\{a,b\\}\n1261\t)\n1262\t(Platt,\n1263\t1999\n1264\t)\n1265\t, ensuring a bounded and monotonic score space suitable for density estimation.\n1266\tAfter that, class-conditional densities are then estimated using Gaussian\n1267\tKDE\n1268\t.\n1269\tWhile the\n1270\tKDE\n1271\t-based method is flexible, it provides no guarantee that\n1272\t𝒞\n1273\t​\n1274\t(\n1275\ts\n1276\ti\n1277\t)\n1278\t\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\n1279\tis monotonic, which is often desirable for calibration.\n1280\tA more constrained form assumes that\n1281\tp\n1282\t~\n1283\t​\n1284\t(\n1285\ts\n1286\ti\n1287\t|\n1288\tH\n1289\t1\n1290\t;\n1291\tθ\n1292\t1\n1293\t)\n1294\t\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1})\n1295\tand\n1296\tp\n1297\t~\n1298\t​\n1299\t(\n1300\ts\n1301\ti\n1302\t|\n1303\tH\n1304\t0\n1305\t;\n1306\tθ\n1307\t0\n1308\t)\n1309\t\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})\n1310\tare Gaussian distributions with a tied standard deviation\n1311\t(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n1312\t2013\n1313\t)\n1314\t, i.e.,\n1315\t(5)\n1316\tp\n1317\t​\n1318\t(\n1319\ts\n1320\ti\n1321\t|\n1322\tH\n1323\t1\n1324\t)\n1325\t=\n1326\t𝒩\n1327\t​\n1328\t(\n1329\ts\n1330\ti\n1331\t|\n1332\tμ\n1333\tf\n1334\t,\n1335\tσ\n1336\t)\n1337\t,\n1338\tp\n1339\t​\n1340\t(\n1341\ts\n1342\ti\n1343\t|\n1344\tH\n1345\t0\n1346\t)\n1347\t=\n1348\t𝒩\n1349\t​\n1350\t(\n1351\ts\n1352\ti\n1353\t|\n1354\tμ\n1355\tr\n1356\t,\n1357\tσ\n1358\t)\n1359\t,\n1360\tp(s_{i}|H_{1})=\\mathcal{N}(s_{i}|\\mu_{f},\\sigma),\\quad p(s_{i}|H_{0})=\\mathcal{N}(s_{i}|\\mu_{r},\\sigma),\n1361\twhere the learnable parameters are\n1362\tθ\n1363\t1\n1364\t=\n1365\t{\n1366\tμ\n1367\tf\n1368\t,\n1369\tσ\n1370\t}\n1371\t\\theta_{1}=\\{\\mu_{f},\\sigma\\}\n1372\tand\n1373\tθ\n1374\t0\n1375\t=\n1376\t{\n1377\tμ\n1378\tr\n1379\t,\n1380\tσ\n1381\t}\n1382\t\\theta_{0}=\\{\\mu_{r},\\sigma\\}\n1383\t.\n1384\tUnder this assumption, the resulting calibration reduces to an affine transformation\n1385\t𝒞\n1386\t​\n1387\t(\n1388\ts\n1389\ti\n1390\t)\n1391\t=\n1392\ta\n1393\t​\n1394\ts\n1395\ti\n1396\t+\n1397\tb\n1398\t\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})=as_{i}+b\n1399\t, where\n1400\t(6)\n1401\ta\n1402\t=\n1403\tμ\n1404\tf\n1405\t−\n1406\tμ\n1407\tr\n1408\tσ\n1409\t2\n1410\t,\n1411\tb\n1412\t=\n1413\t−\n1414\ta\n1415\t​\n1416\t(\n1417\tμ\n1418\tf\n1419\t+\n1420\tμ\n1421\tr\n1422\t)\n1423\t2\n1424\t.\n1425\ta=\\frac{\\mu_{\\text{f}}-\\mu_{\\text{r}}}{\\sigma^{2}},\\quad b=-\\frac{a(\\mu_{\\text{f}}+\\mu_{\\text{r}})}{2}.\n1426\tThis method is known as the constrained, maximum-likelihood, Gaussian (CMLG) calibration\n1427\t(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n1428\t2013\n1429\t)\n1430\t.\n1431\tIn this work, we experiment with KDE and CMLG-based approaches.\n1432\tNote that each method requires a calibration set that is as representative as possible of the target (test) distribution, so that the estimated densities and resulting\n1433\tLLRs\n1434\tare meaningful.\n1435\tIf this set is not representative, the learned densities may be mismatched, leading to unreliable\n1436\tLLRs\n1437\t.\n1438\tThe choice of the calibration set is described in §\n1439\t4\n1440\t.\n1441\t2.4.\n1442\tEnsemble Aggregation Strategy\n1443\tOnce the\n1444\tLLRs\n1445\tare obtained, the straightforward approach is to sum them, motivated by the independent additivity of\n1446\tLLRs\n1447\t(Eq. (\n1448\t4\n1449\t)).\n1450\tWe also consider two alternative strategies.\n1451\tThe first uses a max operator\n1452\t(7)\n1453\tℓ\n1454\t​\n1455\t(\n1456\t𝐱\n1457\t)\n1458\t=\n1459\tmax\n1460\ti\n1461\t⁡\n1462\tℓ\n1463\ti\n1464\t​\n1465\t(\n1466\t𝐱\n1467\t)\n1468\t,\n1469\t\\ell(\\mathbf{x})=\\max_{i}\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),\n1470\twhich retains only the strongest expert response for each sample and assumes that a single artifact may be sufficient for detection.\n1471\tThe second follows a Mixture-of-Experts formulation\n1472\t(Negroni\n1473\tet al.\n1474\t,\n1475\t2025\n1476\t)\n1477\tand applies a learned gating mechanism\n1478\t(8)\n1479\tℓ\n1480\t​\n1481\t(\n1482\t𝐱\n1483\t)\n1484\t=\n1485\t∑\n1486\ti\n1487\tw\n1488\ti\n1489\t​\n1490\t(\n1491\t𝐱\n1492\t)\n1493\t​\n1494\tℓ\n1495\ti\n1496\t​\n1497\t(\n1498\t𝐱\n1499\t)\n1500\t,\n1501\t\\ell(\\mathbf{x})=\\sum_{i}w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),\n1502\twhere sample-dependent weights\n1503\tw\n1504\ti\n1505\t​\n1506\t(\n1507\t𝐱\n1508\t)\n1509\t{w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})}\n1510\tadaptively combine expert\n1511\tLLRs\n1512\tby emphasizing the most relevant ones.\n1513\tIn practice, the calibrated per-expert scores are passed to a linear gating network with dimension equal to the number of experts, which outputs softmax-normalized weights\n1514\t{\n1515\tw\n1516\ti\n1517\t​\n1518\t(\n1519\t𝐱\n1520\t)\n1521\t}\n1522\t\\{w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\}\n1523\t.\n1524\tTable 1\n1525\t.\n1526\tFive artifacts investigated in this study. Abbreviations are defined for statistical parametric speech synthesis (SPSS) and line spectral frequency (LSF). Numbers in brackets for MLP-based expert architectures denote layer sizes.\n1527\tArtifact\n1528\tExample of target algorithm or module\n1529\tRaw features\n1530\tExpert input (#. proxy features)\n1531\tManipulation\n1532\tExpert Architecture\n1533\tF\n1534\t0\n1535\tF_{0}\n1536\tinconsistencies\n1537\tUnit selection\n1538\tF\n1539\t0\n1540\tF_{0}\n1541\ttrajectory\n1542\tvariability, 1st/2nd-order dynamics, ratios (10)\n1543\tshifting, shuffling, compression\n1544\tMLP (10–32–16–1)\n1545\tOversmoothed spectra\n1546\tAcoustic models in SPSS\n1547\tLSFs\n1548\tspatial/temporal spacing dynamics, coeff. variance (13)\n1549\tgaussian smoothing\n1550\tMLP (13–32–16–1)\n1551\tDegrade phase\n1552\tVocoders w/o modeling phase\n1553\tUnwrapped phase\n1554\t-\n1555\tminimum-phase reconstruction\n1556\tLight CNN (LCNN)\n1557\tEnergy inconsistencies\n1558\tUnit selection & SPSS\n1559\tLog-power spec.\n1560\tglobal + band energy, temporal deltas, drop stats (24)\n1561\tlocal attenuations\n1562\tMLP (24–32–16–1)\n1563\tTonal artifacts\n1564\tDNN-based vocoders\n1565\tSpectral fingerprint\n1566\t-\n1567\tinject resonances\n1568\tMLP (225–128–32–1)\n1569\tFigure 3\n1570\t.\n1571\tIllustrative real (top) vs. synthetic (bottom) examples for four\n1572\tof the targeted synthesis artifacts (left to right:\n1573\tF\n1574\t0\n1575\tF_{0}\n1576\tinconsistency, oversmoothing,\n1577\tenergy inconsistency, tonal artifact).\n1578\t3.\n1579\tArtifacts and Expert Models\n1580\tThis section outlines the artifacts and implementation of expert models for speech deepfake detection, designed based on our prior knowledge of speech synthesis algorithms.\n1581\tConsidering the variety of available approaches, we limit this preliminary work to\n1582\tText to Speech (TTS)\n1583\t, the most widely used and extensively studied speech synthesis paradigm, and its generated artifacts. Specifically, we consider\n1584\t5\n1585\t5\n1586\tmajor synthesis artifacts, spanning synthesis paradigms from unit selection to statistical parametric approaches, from linear models to neural methods; their implementation and association with specific deepfake families are detailed for each expert below (summary in\n1587\tTable\n1588\t1\n1589\t).\n1590\t3.1.\n1591\tF0 Inconsistencies\n1592\tGenerating an\n1593\tF\n1594\t0\n1595\tF_{0}\n1596\ttrajectory is essential for natural-sounding speech synthesis\n1597\t(Hirschberg,\n1598\t2002\n1599\t)\n1600\t. A known artifact in unit selection TTS is\n1601\tF\n1602\t0\n1603\tF_{0}\n1604\tinconsistency\n1605\t(Bořil\n1606\tet al.\n1607\t,\n1608\t2017\n1609\t)\n1610\t, perceived as prosodic jumps or discontinuities in synthetic speech. This arises from the concatenation of segmented units.\n1611\tWe extract the\n1612\tF\n1613\t0\n1614\tF_{0}\n1615\ttrajectory using\n1616\tpYIN\n1617\t(Mauch and Dixon,\n1618\t2014\n1619\t)\n1620\t, and apply manipulations within voiced regions. The contour is segmented into 80–160 ms units, and segments are randomly selected with probability\n1621\tp\n1622\tseg\n1623\t∈\n1624\t[\n1625\t0.4\n1626\t,\n1627\t0.7\n1628\t]\n1629\tp_{\\text{seg}}\\in[0.4,0.7]\n1630\t, scaled by factors in\n1631\t[\n1632\t0.87\n1633\t,\n1634\t0.92\n1635\t]\n1636\t[0.87,0.92]\n1637\tor\n1638\t[\n1639\t1.08\n1640\t,\n1641\t1.30\n1642\t]\n1643\t[1.08,1.30]\n1644\t. Selected segments are partially shuffled with probability\n1645\tp\n1646\tshuffle\n1647\t∈\n1648\t[\n1649\t0.2\n1650\t,\n1651\t0.5\n1652\t]\n1653\tp_{\\text{shuffle}}\\in[0.2,0.5]\n1654\t. Alternatively, with fixed probability, the\n1655\tF\n1656\t0\n1657\tF_{0}\n1658\tcontour is compressed toward its median (strength 0.4) and locally smoothed using a three-frame average (strength 0.4), reducing pitch variability. The procedure produces trajectories with either local discontinuities or reduced dynamics. Parameter ranges were empirically set to yield perceptually plausible yet pronounced artifacts for training.\n1659\tWe aggregate\n1660\tF\n1661\t0\n1662\tF_{0}\n1663\tcontours into scalar descriptors, forming a 10-dimensional feature vector for a\n1664\tMulti-Layer Perceptron (MLP)\n1665\tclassifier. Direct use of raw\n1666\tF\n1667\t0\n1668\tF_{0}\n1669\tcontours was ineffective.\n1670\t3.2.\n1671\tOversmoothing\n1672\tIn contrast to unit selection, statistical parametric speech synthesis (SPSS) uses statistical acoustic models to generate smoothed\n1673\tF\n1674\t0\n1675\tF_{0}\n1676\tand spectral trajectories\n1677\t(Tokuda\n1678\tet al.\n1679\t,\n1680\t2013\n1681\t)\n1682\t.\n1683\tHowever, the generated features are often over-smoothed, resulting in muffled synthetic speech\n1684\t(Tokuda\n1685\tet al.\n1686\t,\n1687\t2013\n1688\t)\n1689\t.\n1690\tThis was a central issue when using HMM\n1691\t(Tokuda\n1692\tet al.\n1693\t,\n1694\t2013\n1695\t)\n1696\tand also affects more recent DNN-based acoustic models\n1697\t(Ren\n1698\tet al.\n1699\t,\n1700\t2022\n1701\t)\n1702\t. The same issue can be caused by the DSP-based vocoders. Even if the trend is to switch to DNN-based vocoders, as long as the DNN-based vocoders are trained to minimize the distance of the spectral magnitude between generated and natural speech, the mean-seeking training paradigm is known to produce blurry (or over-smoothed) speech.\n1703\tWe simulate this effect by applying a Gaussian filter to\n1704\tLine Spectral Frequencies (LSF)\n1705\talong the temporal axis, reducing frame-to-frame variation\n1706\t(Merritt and King,\n1707\t2013\n1708\t)\n1709\t.\n1710\tThe filter standard deviation is empirically set to\n1711\t2\n1712\t2\n1713\t.\n1714\tAfter filtering,\n1715\tLSF\n1716\tcoefficients are sorted within each frame to preserve ordering constraints. This yields trajectories with reduced temporal variability, approximating oversmoothed speech.\n1717\tRaw\n1718\tLSFs\n1719\twere ineffective for training: we aggregate frame-level features over time into a 13-dimensional vector for\n1720\tMLP\n1721\t-based classification.\n1722\t3.3.\n1723\tDegraded Phase\n1724\tPhase artifacts commonly arise in three cases: 1) when using vocoders that assume a minimum-phase when reconstructing waveforms from spectral magnitude\n1725\t(Morise\n1726\tet al.\n1727\t,\n1728\t2016\n1729\t)\n1730\t, 2) when using (typically DNN-based) vocoders that do not explicitly generate the phase\n1731\t(Kong\n1732\tet al.\n1733\t,\n1734\t2020\n1735\t)\n1736\t, and 3) when the DNN cannot accurately generate the phase\n1737\t(Siuzdak,\n1738\t2024\n1739\t)\n1740\t.\n1741\tWe model this via controlled lossy phase reconstruction. The waveform is converted to the\n1742\tShort-Time Fourier Transform (STFT)\n1743\tdomain, retaining magnitude while discarding phase. A minimum-phase signal is reconstructed using cepstral processing by enforcing a causal liftering constraint on the log-magnitude spectrum, followed by inverse\n1744\tSTFT\n1745\t. From the reconstructed waveform, the unwrapped phase representation is extracted and used as input to a Light CNN model\n1746\t(Wu\n1747\tet al.\n1748\t,\n1749\t2018\n1750\t)\n1751\t.\n1752\t3.4.\n1753\tEnergy Inconsistencies\n1754\tThis artifact occurs in both unit selection and SPSS-based TTS systems. In unit selection, it may result from imperfect concatenation, while in SPSS it appears as overly uniform regions or abrupt transitions, including unnaturally clean silences.\n1755\tWe simulate this by selecting a short temporal region (\n1756\t6\n1757\t6\n1758\t–\n1759\t30\n1760\t30\n1761\tframes) and attenuating it by a factor drawn from\n1762\t[\n1763\t0.0\n1764\t,\n1765\t0.5\n1766\t]\n1767\t[0.0,\\sqrt{0.5}]\n1768\t, producing local energy drops. The waveform is then converted to a power spectrogram via\n1769\tSTFT\n1770\tand log-scaled. We aggregate it into\n1771\t24\n1772\t24\n1773\tscalar descriptors capturing energy statistics and temporal drops, which are input to a\n1774\tMLP\n1775\t.\n1776\t3.5.\n1777\tTonal Artifacts\n1778\tNarrowband tonal artifacts can occur in neural\n1779\tTTS\n1780\tsystems using DNN-based upsampling modules, such as transposed or subpixel convolutions\n1781\t(Pons\n1782\tet al.\n1783\t,\n1784\t2021\n1785\t)\n1786\t.\n1787\tThese may introduce spectral replicas and uneven overlap, producing spurious narrowband artifacts unrelated to natural harmonics. These are referred to as tonal artifacts\n1788\t(Pons\n1789\tet al.\n1790\t,\n1791\t2021\n1792\t)\n1793\t.\n1794\tWe simulate this by attenuating the waveform by\n1795\t0.05\n1796\t0.05\n1797\t, then adding\n1798\t1\n1799\t1\n1800\t–\n1801\t2\n1802\t2\n1803\tnarrowband resonances using high-Q band-pass filters (1–8 kHz,\n1804\tQ\n1805\t∈\n1806\t[\n1807\t30\n1808\t,\n1809\t80\n1810\t]\n1811\tQ\\in[30,80]\n1812\t, gains\n1813\t[\n1814\t2\n1815\t,\n1816\t5\n1817\t]\n1818\t[2,5]\n1819\t).\n1820\tA nonlinearity increases contrast, followed by normalization, yielding signals dominated by sparse spectral peaks. A spectral fingerprint is extracted following\n1821\t(Afchar\n1822\tet al.\n1823\t,\n1824\t2025\n1825\t)\n1826\t, producing a 1D feature emphasizing these peaks for a\n1827\tMLP\n1828\t.\n1829\tFigure\n1830\t3\n1831\tshows representative real-vs-synthetic examples for four artifacts, illustrating the features used by the corresponding experts; the degraded phase is omitted due to limited suitability for 2D visualization.\n1832\tThe five artifacts are assumed to cover many speech synthesis systems in publicly available deepfake datasets\n1833\t(Wang\n1834\tet al.\n1835\t,\n1836\t2020\n1837\t; Jung\n1838\tet al.\n1839\t,\n1840\t2024\n1841\t)\n1842\t.\n1843\tMany voice conversion (VC) systems relying on statistical models and vocoders, DNN-based or not, may exhibit similar artifacts. A limitation of this approach is that only artifacts known a priori can be modeled by an expert. This is further discussed in §\n1844\t6\n1845\t.\n1846\t4.\n1847\tExperimental Setup\n1848\tThis section outlines the data splits (§\n1849\t4.1\n1850\t), training protocol (§\n1851\t4.2\n1852\t), and evaluation metrics (§\n1853\t4.3\n1854\t) used in our experiments.\n1855\t4.1.\n1856\tDatasets and Partitioning Protocol\n1857\tOur training data consists entirely of real speech drawn from the training sets of ASVspoof 2019\n1858\t(Wang\n1859\tet al.\n1860\t,\n1861\t2020\n1862\t)\n1863\t(clean studio recordings), ASVspoof 5\n1864\t(Wang\n1865\tet al.\n1866\t,\n1867\t2026\n1868\t)\n1869\t(controlled recordings), and SpoofCeleb\n1870\t(Jung\n1871\tet al.\n1872\t,\n1873\t2024\n1874\t)\n1875\t(in-the-wild speech). We trim their leading and trailing silence and apply peak normalization to avoid potential shortcut learning during training\n1876\t(Müller\n1877\tet al.\n1878\t,\n1879\t2021\n1880\t)\n1881\t.\n1882\tTo keep balance, each corpus is subsampled to match the size of the smallest one.\n1883\tThe resulting subsets are split\n1884\t80\n1885\t80\n1886\t/\n1887\t20\n1888\t20\n1889\tat the speaker level into disjoint training and validation sets, and the splits are concatenated across corpora.\n1890\tEvery utterance is duplicated for each expert: one copy is kept unchanged, while the other is modified to match the target artifact.\n1891\tAfter duplication, the final dataset contains\n1892\t24 526\n1893\t24\\,526\n1894\ttraining samples and\n1895\t6242\n1896\t6242\n1897\tvalidation samples.\n1898\tFor calibration, real samples are drawn from the validation set.\n1899\tWhen paired with actual deepfake samples, these are taken either from ASVspoof 2015 (attack S3 for\n1900\tF\n1901\t0\n1902\tF_{0}\n1903\tand energy experts, S10 for the others) or from the ASVspoof 2019 training set (A01 for the tonal artifact expert, A03 for the oversmoothing and phase experts, A04 for the\n1904\tF\n1905\t0\n1906\tF_{0}\n1907\tand energy ones), with A02 excluded for redundancy but retained for testing.\n1908\tFurther details on the choice of these attacks are provided in §\n1909\t5.2\n1910\t.\n1911\tFor evaluation, real samples are taken exclusively from evaluation partitions, while\n1912\tTTS\n1913\tsamples are drawn from the development and evaluation sets for ASVspoof 2019, and from all splits for ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, which are never used for calibration.\n1914\tFor ASVspoof 5, post-processed samples are excluded, as robustness assessment falls outside the scope of this initial analysis.\n1915\tFor both ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, the number of\n1916\tTTS\n1917\tsamples per attack is clipped to the size of the least represented attack class (\n1918\t7760\n1919\t7760\n1920\tand\n1921\t7963\n1922\t7963\n1923\tsamples, respectively), which remains sufficient for meaningful evaluation while balancing class distributions.\n1924\t4.2.\n1925\tTraining Specifications\n1926\tEach expert model is trained for up to\n1927\t100\n1928\t100\n1929\tepochs with early stopping after\n1930\t20\n1931\t20\n1932\tepochs without improvement.\n1933\tThe batch size is\n1934\t128\n1935\t128\n1936\t.\n1937\tOptimization uses AdamW with an initial learning rate of\n1938\t10\n1939\t−\n1940\t3\n1941\t10^{-3}\n1942\t, reduced on plateau with patience\n1943\t10\n1944\t10\n1945\t.\n1946\tTraining uses binary cross-entropy, and selection is based on validation loss.\n1947\tPseudo-fake samples are generated on-the-fly by applying the corresponding expert’s designed manipulation, with dynamic labeling (\n1948\t0\n1949\tfor real,\n1950\t1\n1951\t1\n1952\tfor manipulated).\n1953\tFor\n1954\tMLPs\n1955\tusing scalar features, inputs are standardized using statistics computed on the training set.\n1956\tThe gating network for fusing LLRs (Eq. (\n1957\t8\n1958\t)) is trained separately for\n1959\t10\n1960\t10\n1961\tepochs under the same setup.\n1962\tIn addition to binary cross-entropy, it includes an auxiliary loss enforcing correct expert-artifact attribution, since this time each pseudo-fake contains a single uniformly sampled manipulation.\n1963\tIn terms of calibration, the Gaussian\n1964\tKDE\n1965\tuses a bandwidth of\n1966\t0.1\n1967\t0.1\n1968\t.\n1969\tFor the CMLG approach, the shared variance is experimentally set to\n1970\tσ\n1971\t=\n1972\t0.5\n1973\t\\sigma={0.5}\n1974\t.\n1975\t4.3.\n1976\tEvaluation Metrics\n1977\tWe report\n1978\tArea Under the Curve (AUC)\n1979\tand\n1980\tEqual Error Rate (EER)\n1981\tfor discriminative performance.\n1982\tAUC\n1983\tmeasures ranking quality across thresholds, while\n1984\tEER\n1985\tis the operating point where false acceptance and false rejection rates are equal. Following standard practice in speech deepfake detection, validation\n1986\tEER\n1987\tis also used for model selection.\n1988\tBoth metrics are calibration-blind and depend only on score ordering.\n1989\t4\n1990\t4\n1991\t4\n1992\tAny order-preserving transformation of scores leaves\n1993\tAUC\n1994\tand\n1995\tEER\n1996\tunchanged\n1997\t(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n1998\t2007\n1999\t, § 3.3)\n2000\t.\n2001\tTo assess calibration quality, we additionally report\n2002\tLog-Likelihood Ratio Cost (Cllr)\n2003\t, which evaluates the quality of estimated\n2004\tLLRs\n2005\tin terms of both discrimination and calibration\n2006\t(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2007\t2007\n2008\t)\n2009\t. Lower\n2010\tCllr\n2011\tindicates better-calibrated and more informative scores, while values above\n2012\t1\n2013\t1\n2014\tindicate poor calibration and weak discrimination.\n2015\t5.\n2016\tResults\n2017\tTable 2\n2018\t.\n2019\tExperts performance on ASVspoof 2019 attacks exhibiting their target artifacts, reported as AUC (\n2020\t↑\n2021\t\\uparrow\n2022\t) and EER (\n2023\t↓\n2024\t\\downarrow\n2025\t). Experts were trained using pseudo-fake data. Data from target attacks are unseen.\n2026\tExpert\n2027\tTarget Attack\n2028\tAUC (%)\n2029\tEER (%)\n2030\tF0 Inconsistencies\n2031\tA04 (Unit selection)\n2032\t77.64\n2033\t29.38\n2034\tOversmoothing\n2035\tA03 (DNN + WORLD)\n2036\t97.64\n2037\t6.62\n2038\tDegraded Phase\n2039\tA03 (DNN + WORLD)\n2040\t98.50\n2041\t6.24\n2042\tEnergy Inconsistencies\n2043\tA04 (Unit selection)\n2044\t88.23\n2045\t22.98\n2046\tTonal artifacts\n2047\tA01 (DNN + WaveNet)\n2048\t84.77\n2049\t22.86\n2050\tExperimental results are presented in this section, including the individual evaluation of the artifact-specific experts (§\n2051\t5.1\n2052\t), the optimization of calibration data and methods for the ensemble (§\n2053\t5.2\n2054\t), a comparative analysis of LLR aggregation strategies (§\n2055\t5.3\n2056\t), and an interpretability analysis mapping expert responses to the generation attacks (§\n2057\t5.4\n2058\t).\n2059\t5.1.\n2060\tEvaluation of Individual Expert\n2061\tTo showcase the performance of the artifact-specific experts, we measure their detection results on selected deepfake attacks.\n2062\tFor each expert, we select an ASVspoof 2019 attack that is expected to exhibit the targeted artifact based on its underlying components.\n2063\tSince we are interested in its discrimination power, each experts’ output score\n2064\ts\n2065\ti\n2066\ts_{i}\n2067\tis used to compute the AUC and EER without calibration (§\n2068\t4.3\n2069\t).\n2070\tResults are reported in\n2071\tTable\n2072\t2\n2073\talongside the corresponding synthesis architectures. All experts perform above chance level (\n2074\tAUC\n2075\t=\n2076\tEER\n2077\t=\n2078\t50\n2079\t%\n2080\t\\text{AUC}=\\text{EER}=50\\%\n2081\t), indicating that the chosen expert–artifact assignments are meaningful.\n2082\tAlthough performance remains well below state-of-the-art detectors, this is expected: each expert uses a compact model and targets a single artifact rather than exploiting all available deepfake cues.\n2083\tPlus, experts are trained only on real and pseudo-fake data, not on actual TTS-generated speech (§\n2084\t2.2\n2085\t).\n2086\t5.2.\n2087\tEvaluation of Calibrated Experts in Ensemble\n2088\tEvaluation is first conducted independently for each expert, then outputs are aligned by retaining only samples valid across all experts (discarding those with failed\n2089\tF\n2090\t0\n2091\tF_{0}\n2092\t, which is\n2093\t3.24\n2094\t3.24\n2095\t%).\n2096\tPerformance of the ensemble of experts depends on how well the experts are calibrated and the strategy to fuse the calibrated LLRs. Hence, in this section,\n2097\twe first evaluate calibration choices in\n2098\tFigure\n2099\t4\n2100\tusing a fixed sum aggregation.\n2101\tWe then compare aggregation strategies under the selected calibration setup in the next subsection.\n2102\tThe goodness of calibration is affected by the calibration data as well as the calibration method.\n2103\tIn\n2104\tFigure\n2105\t4\n2106\t, for the two calibration methods using either CMLG or KDE (§\n2107\t2.3\n2108\t), we evaluate\n2109\t4\n2110\t4\n2111\tcalibration set compositions with different data sources:\n2112\t1) pseudo-fakes as in training; 2) ASVspoof 2015 attacks, where each expert uses only a selected attack that matches its target artifact (see §\n2113\t4.1\n2114\t); 3) ASVspoof 2019 attacks under the same expert-specific setup; and 4) a pooled ASVspoof 2019 variant, where the target attacks from all experts are merged into a shared calibration set used for every expert.\n2115\tEach calibration set is further prepared in\n2116\t5\n2117\t5\n2118\tsizes, ranging from\n2119\t10\n2120\t10\n2121\tto\n2122\t1000\n2123\t1000\n2124\tfake utterances per attack.\n2125\tThe real utterances for each set, drawn from validation set, are subsampled to be equal to the number of fake samples.\n2126\tThe evaluation set is ASVspoof 2019.\n2127\tWe observe that only the 4th choice (i.e., the pooled ASVspoof 2019 variant) yields acceptable\n2128\tCllr\n2129\tvalues (below\n2130\t1.0\n2131\t1.0\n2132\t), indicating that a shared calibration set across experts leads to a more stable ensemble, with the best results obtained using the CMLG calibration function.\n2133\tIn this condition, the number of utterances is a negligible factor; the gap between KDE and the CMLG-based calibration methods is also small.\n2134\tSpecifically, the best setup scores\n2135\t19.76\n2136\t19.76\n2137\t%\n2138\tEER\n2139\tand\n2140\t0.638\n2141\t0.638\n2142\tCllr\n2143\t, using only\n2144\t50\n2145\t50\n2146\tsamples per calibration class (i.e., each attack type).\n2147\t5.3.\n2148\tEvaluation of Experts Aggregation\n2149\tUsing the best calibration data and method identified in the previous subsection, we compared three aggregation methods (§\n2150\t2.4\n2151\t) on the ASVspoof 2019 evaluation set. The results presented in\n2152\tTable\n2153\t3\n2154\tshow that summing expert\n2155\tLLRs\n2156\tconsistently achieves the best performance in terms of both\n2157\tEER\n2158\tand Cllr, outperforming max-based and learned gating strategies (\n2159\tTable\n2160\t3\n2161\t).\n2162\tTable 3\n2163\t.\n2164\tEnsemble aggregation strategies comparison on ASVspoof 2019 evaluation set. EER (\n2165\t↓\n2166\t\\downarrow\n2167\t), Cllr (\n2168\t↓\n2169\t\\downarrow\n2170\t).\n2171\tAggregation Method\n2172\tEER (%)\n2173\tCllr\n2174\tSum of Expert LLRs\n2175\t19.76\n2176\t0.638\n2177\tMaximum Expert LLR\n2178\t22.22\n2179\t0.855\n2180\tGating Network\n2181\t21.54\n2182\t0.907\n2183\tFigure 4\n2184\t.\n2185\tEnsemble overall performance on ASVspoof 2019 for different calibration functions, calibration set compositions, and calibration set sizes:\n2186\tEER\n2187\t(left) and\n2188\tCllr\n2189\t(right).\n2190\tCllr\n2191\tvalues above 3 are clipped for visualization.\n2192\t5.4.\n2193\tInterpretability Analysis\n2194\tIn\n2195\tTable\n2196\t4(a)\n2197\t, we report the\n2198\tLLRs\n2199\tof the experts in the best-performing ensemble identified in §\n2200\t5.2\n2201\t, computed for each ASVspoof 2019 attack.\n2202\tOverall, average\n2203\tLLRs\n2204\tremain lower for real than fake samples across all experts, indicating consistent ensemble behavior.\n2205\tAlso, the expert responses are consistent with the characteristics of the underlying generation pipeline of most deepfake attacks: for example, attacks based on HMM/DNN acoustic models consistently yield positive\n2206\tLLRs\n2207\tfrom the oversmoothing expert, while attacks employing DSP-based (WORLD, Vocaine) or DNN vocoders without phase conditioning (Neural Source-Filter) systematically activate the phase expert.\n2208\tThis behavior is expected, as the experts are designed to capture specific types of artifacts, which match the generation techniques represented in the dataset used.\n2209\tMoreover, the strength of the expert responses varies considerably across attacks.\n2210\tSome attacks elicit only weak activations, whereas others trigger multiple experts simultaneously, indicating the coexistence of several artifacts within the same generation pipeline.\n2211\tIn contrast to the other experts, the\n2212\tF\n2213\t0\n2214\tF_{0}\n2215\tone exhibits weaker responses across most attacks, consistent with its lower pre-calibration discriminative performance (\n2216\tTable\n2217\t2\n2218\t) and suggesting that\n2219\tF\n2220\t0\n2221\tF_{0}\n2222\t-related artifacts might be less consistently present or expressed in these attacks.\n2223\tWe then examine the performance of experts on ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, which include newer-generation attacks. As long as the artifacts persist in the newer attacks, they are expected to be spotted by the experts.\n2224\tThe calibration set is kept unchanged from the ASVspoof 2019 setup.\n2225\tOn ASVspoof 5 (\n2226\tTable\n2227\t5\n2228\t), oversmoothing and degraded phase remain consistently activated across many attacks, suggesting partial persistence of these artifacts in newer\n2229\tTTS\n2230\tsystems.\n2231\tIn contrast, energy inconsistencies largely disappear, with only a few isolated exceptions (Tacotron2+WaveGrad exhibits unnaturally blank silences).\n2232\tA similar pattern holds for tonal artifacts, which remain active only for specific systems and partially overlap with those triggering the energy expert, with responses concentrated mainly on Toucan TTS-based attacks across different vocoders.\n2233\tSpoofCeleb (\n2234\tTable\n2235\t6\n2236\t) is overall more challenging but also shows promising results.\n2237\tOversmoothing and degraded phase remain the most prominent artifacts, while energy inconsistencies almost vanish.\n2238\tThe tonal expert responds strongly only to WaveGlow-based systems, consistent with their characteristic audible distortions.\n2239\tNotably, real samples are not always assigned negative\n2240\tLLRs\n2241\tacross experts, suggesting artifact-like characteristics in in-the-wild recordings.\n2242\tWhile not desirable, this is not unexpected, as expert outputs represent evidence of specific artifacts rather than global authenticity.\n2243\tGlobal decisions are instead obtained by aggregating these signals at the ensemble level into\n2244\tH\n2245\t0\n2246\tH_{0}\n2247\t(real) and\n2248\tH\n2249\t1\n2250\tH_{1}\n2251\t(fake), which is meant to help mitigate inconsistencies across individual experts.\n2252\tOverall, the interpretability analysis shows that the artifact-specific experts yield expected results on ASVspoof 2019 by producing positive LLRs to their targeted synthesis pipelines. Furthermore, evaluation on newer datasets demonstrates that these experts also generalize well to varied extents, catching persistent acoustic and phase distortions in modern architectures.\n2253\tTable 4\n2254\t.\n2255\tExpert\n2256\tLLRs\n2257\ton ASVspoof 2019. Higher values indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\n2258\tH\n2259\t1\n2260\tH_{1}\n2261\t).\n2262\tBold\n2263\tvalues indicate positive\n2264\tLLRs\n2265\t.\n2266\t(a)\n2267\tArtifact-specific experts reporting calibrated LLRs per attack. The first three attacks are included in each expert’s calibration set.\n2268\tAvg Real\n2269\tHMM/DNN\n2270\tWaveNet\n2271\tDNN\n2272\tWORLD\n2273\tUnit Selection\n2274\tHMM/DNN\n2275\tWORLD\n2276\tDNN\n2277\tWORLD+GAN\n2278\tHMM/DNN\n2279\tNeural SF\n2280\tDNN\n2281\tVocaine\n2282\tTacotron2\n2283\tWaveRNN\n2284\tTacotron2\n2285\tGriffin-Lim\n2286\tDNN\n2287\tWaveNet\n2288\tAvg Fake\n2289\tF0 Inconsistencies\n2290\t0.00\n2291\t-0.01\n2292\t0.02\n2293\t-0.02\n2294\t0.03\n2295\t0.03\n2296\t0.00\n2297\t0.03\n2298\t0.00\n2299\t0.01\n2300\t0.00\n2301\t0.01\n2302\tOversmoothing\n2303\t-0.10\n2304\t0.05\n2305\t0.30\n2306\t-0.20\n2307\t0.19\n2308\t-0.18\n2309\t0.13\n2310\t0.24\n2311\t-0.16\n2312\t0.08\n2313\t-0.25\n2314\t0.02\n2315\tDegraded Phase\n2316\t-0.39\n2317\t0.04\n2318\t0.71\n2319\t-0.37\n2320\t-0.17\n2321\t0.27\n2322\t0.61\n2323\t1.03\n2324\t0.06\n2325\t0.20\n2326\t-0.10\n2327\t0.23\n2328\tEnergy Inconsistencies\n2329\t-0.49\n2330\t-0.77\n2331\t0.63\n2332\t1.77\n2333\t-0.44\n2334\t-0.32\n2335\t0.01\n2336\t1.25\n2337\t-0.28\n2338\t1.52\n2339\t2.09\n2340\t0.55\n2341\tTonal Artifacts\n2342\t-0.09\n2343\t0.60\n2344\t0.31\n2345\t-0.08\n2346\t0.17\n2347\t0.06\n2348\t0.44\n2349\t0.04\n2350\t-0.10\n2351\t-0.05\n2352\t-0.11\n2353\t0.13\n2354\t(b)\n2355\tAdditional silence duration expert reporting per-attack calibrated LLRs. The first three attacks are part of its calibration set.\n2356\tAvg Real\n2357\tHMM/DNN\n2358\tWaveNet\n2359\tDNN\n2360\tWORLD\n2361\tUnit Selection\n2362\tHMM/DNN\n2363\tWORLD\n2364\tDNN\n2365\tWORLD+GAN\n2366\tHMM/DNN\n2367\tNeural SF\n2368\tDNN\n2369\tVocaine\n2370\tTacotron2\n2371\tWaveRNN\n2372\tTacotron2\n2373\tGriffin-Lim\n2374\tDNN\n2375\tWaveNet\n2376\tAvg Fake\n2377\tSilence Duration Bias\n2378\t-0.19\n2379\t0.48\n2380\t-0.08\n2381\t0.30\n2382\t-0.13\n2383\t1.88\n2384\t-0.03\n2385\t0.91\n2386\t2.27\n2387\t2.05\n2388\t0.59\n2389\t0.82\n2390\tTable 5\n2391\t.\n2392\tExpert\n2393\tLLRs\n2394\ton ASVspoof 5, reported per attack. Top: acoustic model; bottom: vocoder or no distinction. Higher LLRs indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\n2395\tH\n2396\t1\n2397\tH_{1}\n2398\t).\n2399\tBold\n2400\tvalues indicate positive LLRs.\n2401\tAvg Real\n2402\tGlowTTS\n2403\tHiFiGAN\n2404\tGradTTS\n2405\tHiFiGAN\n2406\tVAE\n2407\tHiFiGAN\n2408\tXTTS\n2409\tHiFiGAN\n2410\tVITS\n2411\tHiFiGAN\n2412\tYourTTS\n2413\tYourTTS v2\n2414\tFastPitch\n2415\tHiFiGAN\n2416\tToucan TTS\n2417\tHiFiGAN\n2418\tToucan TTS\n2419\tHiFiGAN v2\n2420\tToucan TTS\n2421\tBigVGAN\n2422\tToucan TTS\n2423\tBigVGAN v2\n2424\tTacotron2\n2425\tWaveGrad\n2426\tUnit Sel.\n2427\tUnit Sel.\n2428\tAvg Fake\n2429\tF0 Inconsistencies\n2430\t-0.01\n2431\t0.00\n2432\t0.00\n2433\t0.01\n2434\t0.01\n2435\t0.02\n2436\t-0.01\n2437\t0.01\n2438\t0.02\n2439\t0.02\n2440\t0.02\n2441\t0.02\n2442\t0.01\n2443\t0.01\n2444\t-0.02\n2445\t0.01\n2446\t0.01\n2447\tOversmoothing\n2448\t-0.16\n2449\t0.30\n2450\t0.24\n2451\t0.11\n2452\t0.18\n2453\t0.21\n2454\t0.08\n2455\t0.06\n2456\t0.46\n2457\t0.23\n2458\t0.23\n2459\t0.30\n2460\t0.20\n2461\t0.13\n2462\t-0.33\n2463\t0.04\n2464\t0.15\n2465\tDegraded Phase\n2466\t-0.14\n2467\t0.17\n2468\t0.24\n2469\t0.06\n2470\t0.30\n2471\t0.05\n2472\t0.23\n2473\t0.18\n2474\t0.35\n2475\t0.26\n2476\t0.26\n2477\t0.17\n2478\t0.29\n2479\t0.03\n2480\t-0.36\n2481\t0.06\n2482\t0.14\n2483\tEnergy Inconsist.\n2484\t-0.25\n2485\t-0.75\n2486\t-0.70\n2487\t-0.57\n2488\t-0.57\n2489\t-0.77\n2490\t-0.89\n2491\t-0.41\n2492\t-0.81\n2493\t0.14\n2494\t0.15\n2495\t0.12\n2496\t0.61\n2497\t2.06\n2498\t-0.17\n2499\t-0.57\n2500\t-0.19\n2501\tTonal Artifacts\n2502\t-0.13\n2503\t-0.22\n2504\t-0.28\n2505\t-0.18\n2506\t-0.24\n2507\t-0.13\n2508\t-0.35\n2509\t-0.13\n2510\t-0.29\n2511\t0.17\n2512\t0.16\n2513\t0.01\n2514\t0.18\n2515\t-0.10\n2516\t-0.13\n2517\t-0.06\n2518\t-0.11\n2519\tTable 6\n2520\t.\n2521\tExpert\n2522\tLLRs\n2523\ton SpoofCeleb, reported per attack. Top: acoustic model; bottom: vocoder or no distinction. Higher LLRs indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\n2524\tH\n2525\t1\n2526\tH_{1}\n2527\t).\n2528\tBold\n2529\tvalues indicate positive LLRs.\n2530\tAvg Real\n2531\tVITS\n2532\tMQTTS\n2533\tVALL-E\n2534\tDelay\n2535\tGradTTS\n2536\tDiffWave\n2537\tMatchaTTS\n2538\tDiffWave\n2539\tGradTTS\n2540\tBigVGAN\n2541\tMatchaTTS\n2542\tBigVGAN\n2543\tGradTTS\n2544\tWaveGlow\n2545\tMatchaTTS\n2546\tWaveGlow\n2547\tGradTTS\n2548\tNSF HiFiGAN\n2549\tMatchaTTS\n2550\tNSF HiFiGAN\n2551\tBVAE-TTS\n2552\tNSF HiFiGAN\n2553\tGradTTS\n2554\tHiFiGAN\n2555\tMatchaTTS\n2556\tHiFiGAN\n2557\tBVAE-TTS\n2558\tHiFiGAN\n2559\tMS-Transf\n2560\tTransfTTS\n2561\tPWG\n2562\tAvg Fake\n2563\tF0 Inconsistencies\n2564\t0.01\n2565\t0.00\n2566\t0.01\n2567\t0.01\n2568\t0.01\n2569\t0.00\n2570\t0.01\n2571\t0.00\n2572\t0.01\n2573\t-0.02\n2574\t-0.02\n2575\t0.01\n2576\t0.01\n2577\t0.01\n2578\t0.01\n2579\t0.01\n2580\t0.01\n2581\t0.01\n2582\t0.01\n2583\t0.01\n2584\tOversmoothing\n2585\t0.31\n2586\t0.14\n2587\t0.25\n2588\t0.24\n2589\t0.22\n2590\t0.05\n2591\t0.16\n2592\t0.22\n2593\t0.26\n2594\t-0.04\n2595\t0.29\n2596\t0.33\n2597\t0.32\n2598\t0.30\n2599\t0.33\n2600\t0.33\n2601\t0.35\n2602\t0.31\n2603\t0.32\n2604\t0.24\n2605\tDegraded Phase\n2606\t-0.06\n2607\t0.24\n2608\t0.25\n2609\t0.07\n2610\t0.32\n2611\t0.00\n2612\t0.24\n2613\t-0.22\n2614\t0.05\n2615\t-0.05\n2616\t-0.13\n2617\t0.44\n2618\t-0.06\n2619\t-0.20\n2620\t-0.06\n2621\t0.42\n2622\t-0.03\n2623\t-0.05\n2624\t-0.05\n2625\t0.07\n2626\tEnergy Inconsist.\n2627\t-1.10\n2628\t-0.74\n2629\t-0.41\n2630\t-0.86\n2631\t-0.79\n2632\t-1.16\n2633\t-0.98\n2634\t-0.97\n2635\t-0.86\n2636\t-1.03\n2637\t-0.95\n2638\t-0.94\n2639\t-1.10\n2640\t-1.09\n2641\t-1.10\n2642\t-0.94\n2643\t-1.10\n2644\t-1.10\n2645\t-1.10\n2646\t-0.96\n2647\tTonal Artifacts\n2648\t-0.36\n2649\t0.18\n2650\t-0.08\n2651\t-0.08\n2652\t-0.01\n2653\t0.08\n2654\t0.10\n2655\t-0.01\n2656\t-0.05\n2657\t3.01\n2658\t3.02\n2659\t-0.11\n2660\t-0.36\n2661\t-0.35\n2662\t-0.35\n2663\t-0.10\n2664\t-0.34\n2665\t-0.36\n2666\t-0.35\n2667\t0.21\n2668\t5.5.\n2669\tInterpretability for Shortcut Diagnosis\n2670\tAll experts in this work operate on features treated as nuisance-robust representations and are not intended to exploit any dataset-specific shortcuts\n2671\t(Sahidullah\n2672\tet al.\n2673\t,\n2674\t2025\n2675\t)\n2676\t, but we can add experts to diagnose potential shortcuts.\n2677\tThe impact of a shortcut can be revealed by comparing 1) the values of calibrated\n2678\tLLRs\n2679\tfrom the suspected expert with others and 2) the ensemble’s performance with and without the suspected expert. The latter can be easily done since the framework is inherently modular: expert outputs are combined as a linear sum, and an expert can be directly added to or removed from the ensemble. No modification or retraining is required for other experts.\n2680\tAs a demonstration, we introduce a 6th control expert targeting a known dataset bias related to silence-duration patterns\n2681\t(Müller\n2682\tet al.\n2683\t,\n2684\t2021\n2685\t)\n2686\t.\n2687\tSilence intervals are extracted by applying a voice activity detector and deriving complementary non-speech regions.\n2688\tTo generate pseudofakes, the silence-duration sequence is stochastically compressed toward its mean, perturbed with controlled noise, truncated for overly long pauses, and constrained at sequence boundaries.\n2689\tThis reflects the tendency of synthetic speech to exhibit reduced variability and shorter silences, particularly at leading and trailing positions\n2690\t(Müller\n2691\tet al.\n2692\t,\n2693\t2021\n2694\t)\n2695\t.\n2696\tFeatures are summarized into\n2697\t10\n2698\t10\n2699\tproxies and classified using a dedicated MLP (10–32–16–1).\n2700\tThis expert is designed, trained, and calibrated independently from the others.\n2701\tIts calibration set differs slightly from those of the other experts, as real samples are drawn exclusively from ASVspoof 2019 due to the dataset-dependent nature of the targeted artifact.\n2702\tResults on ASVspoof 2019\n2703\tTTS\n2704\tattacks in\n2705\tTable\n2706\t4(b)\n2707\tshow expected traits of shortcut: particularly for Tacotron2 + WaveRNN, where previous experts were weak, the added expert provides very strong ‘evidence’ (\n2708\tLLR\n2709\t¿\n2710\t2\n2711\t2\n2712\t). At the ensemble level, the expert reduced the EER to around 12%. However, since the expert only relies on silence duration, the large magnitude of\n2713\tLLR\n2714\tand reduced EER suggest that the expert is exploiting the dataset-specific shortcut.\n2715\tWe show the new ensemble performance in\n2716\tFigure\n2717\t5\n2718\t, along with the confusion matrix at threshold\n2719\t0\n2720\t.\n2721\tFigure 5\n2722\t.\n2723\tEnsemble overall performance on ASVspoof 2019 after adding the sixth expert. ROC curve and confusion matrix (LLR scores threshold set at 0).\n2724\t6.\n2725\tConclusions\n2726\tWe proposed an interpretable speech deepfake detection framework based on artifact-specific expert models. The system decomposes detection into learning and recognition of predefined synthesis artifacts, each modeled by a dedicated classifier trained on pseudo-fake data.\n2727\tExpert outputs are calibrated into\n2728\tLLRs\n2729\t, providing a common interpretable measure of evidence linking decisions to artifact presence.\n2730\tExperiments show that (i) experts reliably detect their target artifacts, (ii) calibration is essential for meaningful comparison across experts, and (iii)\n2731\tLLR\n2732\tsummation is the most effective aggregation strategy.\n2733\tThe framework provides an interpretable mechanism for identifying synthesis artifacts while maintaining a modular architecture that can be extended as new artifact classes emerge. It also helps to diagnose potential dataset shortcuts.\n2734\tFuture work will focus on broadening the range of artifact-specific experts to capture the increasingly diverse characteristics of modern speech synthesis systems. Adapting automated rule-learning frameworks from the visual domain\n2735\t(Raza\n2736\tet al.\n2737\t,\n2738\t2024\n2739\t)\n2740\tto extract and compose speech anomalies into human-interpretable artifacts represents a promising direction for long-term, extendable development.\n2741\tOther topics, such as improved calibration and refined expert pipelines, are also expected to further boost the overall performance.\n2742\tOwing to its additive and modular design, these developments can be incorporated by introducing new experts while preserving the interpretability and extensibility of the overall framework.\n2743\tReferences\n2744\tD. Afchar, G. Meseguer-Brocal, K. Akesbi, and R. Hennequin (2025)\n2745\tA Fourier explanation of AI-music artifacts\n2746\t.\n2747\tIn\n2748\tProceedings of the International Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR)\n2749\t,\n2750\tCited by:\n2751\t§3.5\n2752\t.\n2753\tF. Alonso-Fernandez, K. B. Raja, R. Raghavendra, C. Busch, J. Bigun, R. Vera-Rodriguez, and J. Fierrez (2022)\n2754\tCross-sensor periocular biometrics in a global pandemic: Comparative benchmark and novel multialgorithmic approach\n2755\t.\n2756\tInformation Fusion\n2757\t83-84\n2758\t,\n2759\tpp. 110–130\n2760\t.\n2761\tCited by:\n2762\t§2.1\n2763\t.\n2764\tA. Bassit, F. Hahn, J. Peeters, T. Kevenaar, R. Veldhuis, and A. Peter (2021)\n2765\