works for synthetic speech detection: a likelihood-ratio-based approach\n2840\t.\n2841\tIn\n2842\tAudio Engineering Society (AES) International Conference on Audio Forensics\n2843\t,\n2844\tCited by:\n2845\t§2.3.2\n2846\t.\n2847\tW. Ge, M. Todisco, and N. Evans (2022)\n2848\tExplainable deepfake and spoofing detection: an attack analysis using shapley additive explanations\n2849\t.\n2850\tIn\n2851\tThe Speaker and Language Recognition Workshop (Odyssey 2022)\n2852\t,\n2853\tpp. 70–76\n2854\t.\n2855\tCited by:\n2856\t§1\n2857\t.\n2858\tW. Ge, X. Wang, X. Liu, and J. Yamagishi (2025)\n2859\tPost-training for deepfake speech detection\n2860\t.\n2861\tIn\n2862\tIEEE Automatic Speech Recognition and Understanding Workshop (ASRU)\n2863\t,\n2864\tpp. 1–8\n2865\t.\n2866\tCited by:\n2867\t§1\n2868\t.\n2869\tH. Gu, J. Yi, C. Wang, J. Tao, Z. Lian, J. He, Y. Ren, Y. Chen, and Z. Wen (2025)\n2870\tALLM4ADD: unlocking the capabilities of audio large language models for audio deepfake detection\n2871\t.\n2872\tIn\n2873\tProceedings of the 33rd ACM International Conference on Multimedia\n2874\t,\n2875\tpp. 11736–11745\n2876\t.\n2877\tCited by:\n2878\t§1\n2879\t.\n2880\tJ. Hirschberg (2002)\n2881\tCommunication and prosody: functional aspects of prosody\n2882\t.\n2883\tSpeech Communication\n2884\t36\n2885\t(\n2886\t1–2\n2887\t),\n2888\tpp. 31–43\n2889\t.\n2890\tCited by:\n2891\t§3.1\n2892\t.\n2893\tW. Huang, Y. Gu, Z. Wang, H. Zhu, and Y. Qian (2025)\n2894\tSpeechFake: A large-scale multilingual speech deepfake dataset toward cutting-edge speech generation methods\n2895\t.\n2896\tIn\n2897\tProceedings of the 63rd Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics\n2898\t,\n2899\tpp. 9985–9998\n2900\t.\n2901\tCited by:\n2902\t§1\n2903\t.\n2904\tE. T. Jaynes (2003)\n2905\tProbability theory: The logic of science\n2906\t.\n2907\tCambridge university press\n2908\t.\n2909\tCited by:\n2910\t§2.1\n2911\t.\n2912\tJ. Jung, H. Heo, H. Tak, H. Shim, J. S. Chung, B. Lee, H. Yu, and N. Evans (2022)\n2913\tAASIST: audio anti-spoofing using integrated spectro-temporal graph attention networks\n2914\t.\n2915\tIn\n2916\tIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP)\n2917\t,\n2918\tpp. 6367–6371\n2919\t.\n2920\tCited by:\n2921\t§1\n2922\t.\n2923\tJ. Jung, Y. Wu, X. Wang, J. Kim, S. Maiti, Y. Matsunaga, H. Shim, J. Tian, N. Evans, J. S. Chung,\n2924\tet al.\n2925\t(2024)\n2926\tSpoofCeleb: speech deepfake detection and sasv in the wild\n2927\t.\n2928\tIEEE Open Journal of Signal Processing\n2929\t6\n2930\t,\n2931\tpp. 68–77\n2932\t.\n2933\tCited by:\n2934\t§3.5\n2935\t,\n2936\t§4.1\n2937\t.\n2938\tJ. Kong, J. Kim, and J. Bae (2020)\n2939\tHiFi-GAN: generative adversarial networks for efficient and high fidelity speech synthesis\n2940\t.\n2941\tIn\n2942\tProc. NIPS\n2943\t,\n2944\tVol.\n2945\t33\n2946\t,\n2947\tpp. 17022–17033\n2948\t.\n2949\tCited by:\n2950\t§3.3\n2951\t.\n2952\tC. L. Machado, X. Wang, and J. Yamagishi (2025)\n2953\tTowards a transparent and interpretable strategy for spoofed speech detection\n2954\t.\n2955\tIn\n2956\tThe 33rd Annual Conference of the International Association for Forensic Phonetics and Acoustics (IAFPA)\n2957\t,\n2958\tCited by:\n2959\t§1\n2960\t.\n2961\tM. Mandasari (2018)\n2962\tSpeaker recognition system in forensic conditions: The calibration and evaluation of the likelihood ratio\n2963\t.\n2964\tphd\n2965\t,\n2966\tRadboud University\n2967\t.\n2968\tCited by:\n2969\t§2.3.1\n2970\t.\n2971\tM. Mauch and S. Dixon (2014)\n2972\tpYIN: A fundamental frequency estimator using probabilistic threshold distributions\n2973\t.\n2974\tIn\n2975\tIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP)\n2976\t,\n2977\tpp. 659–663\n2978\t.\n2979\tCited by:\n2980\t§3.1\n2981\t.\n2982\tT. Merritt and S. King (2013)\n2983\tInvestigating the shortcomings of hmm synthesis\n2984\t.\n2985\tIn\n2986\tProceedings of 8th ISCA Speech Synthesis Workshop\n2987\t,\n2988\tpp. 185–190\n2989\t.\n2990\tCited by:\n2991\t§3.2\n2992\t.\n2993\tJ. Mishra, M. Chhibber, H. Shim, and T. H. Kinnunen (2026)\n2994\tTowards explainable spoofed speech attribution and detection: a probabilistic approach for characterizing speech synthesizer components\n2995\t.\n2996\tComputer Speech & Language\n2997\t95\n2998\t,\n2999\tpp. 101840\n3000\t.\n3001\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a319e1b7-9b31-44c3-8de5-779e67f5027e", "uuid": "a3b04008-1720-489f-9210-dfb0f8d34752", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:06:46.645Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/a319e1b7-9b31-44c3-8de5-779e67f5027e/tool-results/b54wc8o39.txt", "content": "Toward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\nTitle:\nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\nDescription:\narXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\nLearn more\n×\nLicense: CC BY 4.0\narXiv:2607.21127v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026\nToward Interpretable Speech Deepfake Detection using Artifact-Specific Experts and Calibrated Detection Scores\nViola Negroni\nviola.negroni@polimi.it\n0009-0000-2483-4366\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n,\nXin Wang\nwangxin@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\n,\nWanying Ge\ngewanying@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\n,\nPaolo Bestagini\npaolo.bestagini@polimi.it\n0000-0003-0406-0222\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n,\nJunichi Yamagishi\njyamagis@nii.ac.jp\nNational Institute of Informatics\nTokyo\nJapan\nand\nStefano Tubaro\nstefano.tubaro@polimi.it\n0000-0002-1990-9869\nDEIB, Politecnico di Milano\nMilano\nItaly\n(2026)\nAbstract.\nIn this work, we propose an interpretable framework for speech deepfake detection based on artifact-specific expert models.\nRather than relying on black-box decisions, the framework provides human-understandable evidence, which is critical in high-stakes settings.\nEach expert is trained to detect a specific speech synthesis artifact, and its output is calibrated into a log-likelihood ratio that serves as an interpretable evidence score.\nWe evaluate five artifact-specific experts and show that, with proper calibration, they can capture their target artifacts and produce meaningful evidence.\nImportantly, each expert estimates only the presence of its assigned artifact rather than directly performing the final decision.\nTheir outputs are aggregated into an ensemble to produce the actual real-versus-fake classification, while maintaining interpretability by indicating how strongly each expert supports or contradicts a fake classification.\nResults show that artifact-specific experts capture interpretable signals of synthetic speech across multiple generation pipelines.\nSpeech Deepfake Detection, Interpretability, Synthesis Artifacts, Text-to-speech, Audio Forensics\n†\n†\ncopyright:\nacmlicensed\n†\n†\njournalyear:\n2026\n†\n†\ndoi:\nXXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n†\n†\nccs:\nSecurity and privacy Spoofing attacks\n†\n†\nccs:\nSecurity and privacy Biometrics\n†\n†\nccs:\nApplied computing Computer forensics\n1.\nIntroduction\nSpeech deepfake detection aims to identify synthetic speech used for malicious purposes, such as impersonation, fraud, and misinformation.\nOver recent years, substantial progress has been achieved in detection performance\n(Jung\net al.\n,\n2022\n; Huang\net al.\n,\n2025\n; Xiao and Das,\n2025\n)\n. This progress has coincided with a shift from simpler machine learning approaches to increasingly complex\nDeep Learning (DL)\n-based systems, ranging from supervised models\n(Tak\net al.\n,\n2021\n; Jung\net al.\n,\n2022\n)\nto large pre-trained models\n(Wang and Yamagishi,\n2022\n; Ge\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\nand, more recently, large language model-based methods\n(Gu\net al.\n,\n2025\n; Xie\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\n.\nIn parallel, manually designed features\n(Borrelli\net al.\n,\n2021\n; Todisco\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\nhave progressively been replaced by learned self-supervised representations\n(Salvi\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\n.\nWhile these developments have improved performance, they have also reduced interpretability compared to classical approaches (e.g., decision trees and phonetic features\n(Machado\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n).\nIn high-stakes applications such as deepfake detection, where decisions may carry forensic, legal, or societal consequences, this lack of transparency becomes particularly problematic.\nSome post-hoc methods have been proposed to explain the behavior of black-box detectors\n(Ge\net al.\n,\n2022\n)\n.\nHowever, relying on post-hoc explanations for black-box models is fundamentally limited\n(Rudin,\n2019\n)\n, since these explanations do not guarantee faithful correspondence with the actual reasoning process of the classifier.\nInstead, interpretability should be embedded directly into the model design, so that the explanation itself corresponds to the mechanism used to reach the decision.\nRecent work has explored related directions.\nOne approach\n(Mishra\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\naugments real/fake detectors with auxiliary classifiers predicting attributes of the synthesis process, such as TTS vs. voice conversion and the generator’s DNN type. Another\n(Negroni\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\nadds branches predicting acoustic features and per-frame weights.\nWhile these methods provide additional signals, the resulting explanations remain coarse and do not directly expose nor quantify the evidence driving individual detection decisions.\nOur proposed framework explicitly targets intrinsically interpretable detection.\nAs shown in\nFigure\n1\n, the task is decomposed into predefined\nsynthesis artifacts\n, each handled by a dedicated expert model.\nExpert outputs are calibrated into interpretable\nLog-Likelihood Ratios (LLRs)\n, quantifying evidence for the presence of each artifact, and then aggregated into a global score.\nTo the best of our knowledge, this is the first work to frame speech deepfake detection as explicit artifact identification followed by\nLLR\n-based aggregation.\nConventional\nDL\n-based models implicitly learn artifacts without defining or isolating them, making it unclear whether decisions rely on meaningful cues or spurious correlations\n(Sahidullah\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n.\nThis raises concerns about their reliability.\nIn contrast, our approach is expected to mitigate the issue by replacing implicit artifact learning with an explicit formulation, where predefined synthesis artifacts are detected individually, and their evidence is combined via a principled\nLLR\n-based framework.\nRelatedly, the\nBinary-attribute-based-LR (BA-LR)\nframework for speaker verification\n(Ben-Amor\net al.\n,\n2023\n)\nalso produces attribute-specific LLRs, but it decomposes scores from a pretrained verifier using a surrogate model.\nThis top-down approach differs from ours, which directly computes and aggregates individual\nLLRs\nin a bottom-up manner.\nAs this is a preliminary, exploratory study, we focus on a set of artifacts well understood in the speech synthesis field.\nExperimental results show that the proposed method achieves meaningful detection performance while enabling the contribution of each expert to the final decision to be directly quantified and interpreted in terms of the presence of each artifact.\nAdditionally, the framework is modular by design, and new experts can be directly incorporated.\nThis additive design is well-suited to real-world deployment and may also facilitate the identification of dataset shortcuts and spurious correlations (see §\n5.5\n).\nFigure 1\n.\nOverview of the proposed framework for interpretable speech deepfake detection.\n2.\nProposed Method\nIn this section, we describe the proposed interpretable speech deepfake detection framework (detailed representation in\nFigure\n2\n) in the order of the problem formulation (§\n2.1\n), the design of artifact-specific expert models (§\n2.2\n), their calibration into\nLLRs\n(§\n2.3\n), and the aggregation of\nLLRs\n(§\n2.4\n).\n2.1.\nProblem Formulation\nGiven a discrete speech signal\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\nwith class label\ny\n∈\n{\n0\n,\n1\n}\ny\\in\\{0,1\\}\n, we consider two hypotheses:\nH\n0\nH_{0}\ndenotes the real class (\ny\n=\n0\ny=0\n) where\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\nis free of artifacts; and\nH\n1\nH_{1}\ndenotes the fake class (\ny\n=\n1\ny=1\n) where\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\ncontains synthesis artifacts.\nThe task is to determine the class of\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\nusing multiple artifact-specific experts.\nEach expert\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\ntargets a particular synthesis artifact and uses\nℱ\ni\n\\mathcal{F}_{i}\nto extract features relevant to the detection of the artifact. The raw output score of each expert\ns\ni\n≜\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\ns_{i}\\triangleq\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))\nis then calibrated towards a\nLLR\nusing a calibration function\n𝒞\n\\mathcal{C}\n, which can be written as\n(1)\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n≈\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n0\n)\n.\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{0})}.\nAn ideal LLR quantifies the evidence in favor of artifact presence, which is the foundation for ensembling multiple experts.\nAn ensemble with\nI\nI\nexperts can produce a system-level LLR\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\nby\n(2)\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\n𝐱\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\n𝐱\n|\nH\n0\n)\n\\displaystyle\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathbf{x}|H_{1})}{p(\\mathbf{x}|H_{0})}\n≈\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\n{\nℱ\n1\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n⋯\n,\nℱ\nI\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\n{\nℱ\n1\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n⋯\n,\nℱ\nI\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n|\nH\n0\n)\n\\displaystyle\\approx\\log\\frac{p(\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}|H_{1})}{p(\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}|H_{0})}\n(3)\n≈\n∑\ni\n=\n1\nI\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n0\n)\n.\n\\displaystyle\\approx\\sum_{i=1}^{I}\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{0})}.\nThe first approximation (Eq. (\n2\n)) assumes that the set of artifacts\n{\nℱ\n1\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n⋯\n,\nℱ\nI\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n\\{\\mathcal{F}_{1}(\\mathbf{x}),\\cdots,\\mathcal{F}_{I}(\\mathbf{x})\\}\nsummarizes all the necessary artifacts to make the decision. The second approximation (Eq. (\n3\n)) assumes independence of the feature distributions given the hypothesis (\nH\n0\nH_{0}\nor\nH\n1\nH_{1}\n), which is known as the\nindependent additivity\nof individual LLRs\n(Jaynes,\n2003\n)\nand is widely used in multi-factor biometric authentication\n(Alonso-Fernandez\net al.\n,\n2022\n; Bassit\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\n1\n1\n1\nThe above formulation also differ from\nBA-LR\n(Ben-Amor\net al.\n,\n2023\n)\n, which solves the problem of decomposing\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\ninto\n{\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n∣\nH\n0\n)\n}\ni\n=\n1\nI\n\\{\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\mid H_{0})}\\}_{i=1}^{I}\nand learning the mapping from each\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\nto a specific speaker attribute.\nIn the context of deepfake detection, if each expert focuses on a different artifact and captures a different aspect of the signal,\nthe independent additivity of LLRs is a practical approximation.\nGiven\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})\n, the ensemble system can decide\nH\n0\nH_{0}\nand\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nby comparing it with a pre-defined threshold following the Bayes decision theory.\n2\n2\n2\nSetting the threshold based on priors is well discussed in other literature\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2007\n, Eq. (6))\n. The threshold used in this study is discussed in §\n4\nSeveral technical questions need to be addressed.\nFirst, we need to design the experts and their corresponding\n{\nℱ\ni\n}\n\\{\\mathcal{F}_{i}\\}\n. Second, we need to properly implement the calibration function\n𝒞\n\\mathcal{C}\nso that\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n≈\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n.\nFinally, since LLRs are assumed to be independent, we may try alternative ways to fuse the LLRs.\n2.2.\nExpert Model Design\nTaking advantage of the knowledge from the speech synthesis field, we design experts and their corresponding\n{\nℱ\ni\n}\n\\{\\mathcal{F}_{i}\\}\nfor a set of well-known artifacts.\nAn artifact might be regarded as\na systematic and detectable deviation from real speech\n, potentially arising at different stages of synthesis (e.g., acoustic modeling or waveform generation).\nFor each type of artifact, we construct an expert\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nthat targets its detection.\nThe resulting set of experts forms the building block of our method, allowing decisions to be interpreted in terms of the presence or absence of specific artifacts in the given speech.\nHowever, it is not straightforward to learn the parameters of an artifact-specific\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nfrom fake data that is synthesized by existing speech generative models, because they may carry compounded artifacts.\nMoreover, training on real and fake samples offers limited control over the learned discriminative cues, and the model may end up relying on dataset-specific biases unrelated to the task\n(Sahidullah\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n.\nTo address this issue, we train each expert using a pseudo-fake generation strategy, in which the target artifact is simulated through a controlled manipulation applied to real speech.\nThis ensures that the simulated artifact is the only difference between real and pseudo-fake data, encouraging each expert to focus on the intended artifact.\nSpecifically, for a given artifact, we create manipulated speech from real utterances such that the applied manipulation emulates the target artifact while leaving other characteristics unchanged. To further enforce specialization, the input feature representation is deliberately designed to emphasize the artifact of interest and suppress unrelated information.\nFormally, for a given\n𝐱\n\\mathbf{x}\n, we derive two training inputs for\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nusing the artifact-specific feature extraction\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\cdot)\nand manipulation\nℳ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{M}_{i}(\\cdot)\n:\n𝐳\n0\n=\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\mathbf{z}_{0}=\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\nand\n𝐳\n1\n=\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\nℳ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\n\\mathbf{z}_{1}=\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathcal{M}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))\n, with labels\ny\n=\n0\ny=0\nand\ny\n=\n1\ny=1\n, respectively. Each expert\nℰ\ni\n​\n(\n⋅\n)\n\\mathcal{E}_{i}(\\cdot)\nis then trained as a binary classifier using multiple pairs of\n𝐳\n0\n\\mathbf{z}_{0}\nand\n𝐳\n1\n\\mathbf{z}_{1}\n.\nUsing pseudo-fake data not only facilitates the learning of artifact-specific experts but also simplifies data collection.\nThe set of artifacts investigated in this study is explained in §\n3\n.\nFigure 2\n.\nDetailed representation of the proposed framework (training and inference).\n2.3.\nModel Calibration\n2.3.1.\nMotivation\nAs mentioned in §\n2.1\n, we calibrate\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nfrom each expert so that its calibrated version better approximates\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n. In fact, using LLRs is not only preferred when fusing multiple experts (Eq. (\n3\n)) but also widely recognized by the forensic community as the proper way of representing “the value of the evidence\n…\n\\dots\nto be reported to a court of law”\n(Ramos\net al.\n,\n2017\n, § 14.3)\n.\nTo briefly explain the reasons, we note that making a Bayes decision given a single expert requires a comparison between the posterior odds\nlog\n⁡\nP\n​\n(\nH\n1\n|\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\nP\n​\n(\nH\n0\n|\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n)\n\\log\\frac{P(H_{1}|\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))}{P(H_{0}|\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x}))}\nagainst the decision cost ratio\nlog\n⁡\nC\n0\nC\n1\n\\log\\frac{C_{0}}{C_{1}}\n, where\nC\n0\nC_{0}\nand\nC\n1\nC_{1}\nare the costs for falsely classifying\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nand\nH\n0\nH_{0}\n, respectively.\nUsing Bayes’ rule, we get an equivalent decision strategy, which can be written as\n(4)\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n≜\nlog\n⁡\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n1\n)\np\n​\n(\nℱ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n|\nH\n0\n)\n​\n≷\nH\n0\nH\n1\n​\nlog\n⁡\nC\n0\nC\n1\n+\nlog\n⁡\nP\n​\n(\nH\n0\n)\nP\n​\n(\nH\n1\n)\n,\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\triangleq\\log\\frac{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{1})}{p(\\mathcal{F}_{i}(\\mathbf{x})|H_{0})}\\underset{H_{0}}{\\overset{H_{1}}{\\gtrless}}\\log\\frac{C_{0}}{C_{1}}+\\log\\frac{P(H_{0})}{P(H_{1})},\nwhere\nP\n​\n(\nH\n0\n)\nP(H_{0})\nand\nP\n​\n(\nH\n1\n)\nP(H_{1})\ndenote the class priors.\nThe main reason for producing and reporting LLRs is that they provide a\nuniversal interpretation\nof the strength of evidence in favor of a hypothesis\n(Ramos\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\n.\nThis interpretation is independent of the data prior probability, the backbone model, or input representation: for instance,\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\n0\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=0\ndoes not favor either one of the hypotheses, and\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\nlog\n⁡\n3\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=\\log 3\nmeans that “the evidence supports\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nagainst\nH\n0\nH_{0}\nwith a degree of 3 versus 1”.\n3\n3\n3\nAccording to the guideline of the European network of forensic science institutes\n(Champod\net al.\n,\n2016\n)\n, we may also verbally explain the support of evidence represented by the LLR.\nFor example,\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n>\nlog\n⁡\n10\n6\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})>\\log 10^{6}\ndenotes\nextremely strong\nsupport to\nH\n1\nH_{1}\nwhile\nlog\n⁡\n10\n4\n>\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n>\nlog\n⁡\n10\n3\n\\log 10^{4}>\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})>\\log 10^{3}\ndenotes\nmoderately strong\n.\nUniversal interpretation\nalso means that the LLRs of different experts are on the same scale and can be directly summed together (Eq. (\n3\n)).\nA further advantage, as shown in Eq. (\n4\n), is the separation between modeling and decision-making: the forensic examiner produces the LLR (left-hand side of Eq. (\n4\n)), while the decision threshold (right-hand side), based on priors and costs, is set by the court\n(Ramos\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\n.\nA binary classifier does not necessarily produce LLRs.\nFor instance, a probability-like\ns\ni\n∈\n[\n0\n,\n1\n]\ns_{i}\\in[0,1]\ncannot be interpreted as a log-likelihood ratio\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐳\n)\n∈\n(\n−\n∞\n,\n∞\n)\n\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{z})\\in(-\\infty,\\infty)\n.\nEven if transformed into an unbounded score, for example, using\nf\n​\n(\nx\n)\n=\nlog\n⁡\nx\n1\n−\nx\nf(x)=\\log\\frac{x}{1-x}\nfor\nx\n∈\n(\n0\n,\n1\n)\nx\\in(0,1)\n, the score still may not satisfy the statistical properties of true LLRs (e.g., “the LLR of the LLR is the LLR”\n(Mandasari,\n2018\n)\n).\n2.3.2.\nMethods\nThere are many possible ways of calibrating\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nso that\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n≈\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\\approx\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\n.\nWe consider a generative approach\n(Brummer\net al.\n,\n2014\n)\n, which treats the expert outputs\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nas samples generated from class-conditional scores distributions\n{\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n;\nθ\n1\n)\n,\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n;\nθ\n0\n)\n}\n\\{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1}),\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})\\}\n: after estimating the two distributions, we calibrate by\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n=\nlog\n⁡\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n;\nθ\n1\n)\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n;\nθ\n0\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})=\\log\\frac{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1})}{\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})}\n.\nIn practice, we need to choose the parametric form of such distributions.\nA fully flexible approach models each class distribution free-form, e.g., via\nKernel Density Estimation (KDE)\n(Cuccovillo\net al.\n,\n2023\n)\n.\nScores\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nare first mapped via Platt scaling (i.e., logistic regression\n1\n1\n+\nexp\n⁡\n(\na\n​\ns\ni\n+\nb\n)\n\\frac{1}{1+\\exp(as_{i}+b)}\nwith learned parameters\n{\na\n,\nb\n}\n\\{a,b\\}\n)\n(Platt,\n1999\n)\n, ensuring a bounded and monotonic score space suitable for density estimation.\nAfter that, class-conditional densities are then estimated using Gaussian\nKDE\n.\nWhile the\nKDE\n-based method is flexible, it provides no guarantee that\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})\nis monotonic, which is often desirable for calibration.\nA more constrained form assumes that\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n;\nθ\n1\n)\n\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{1};\\theta_{1})\nand\np\n~\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n;\nθ\n0\n)\n\\tilde{p}(s_{i}|H_{0};\\theta_{0})\nare Gaussian distributions with a tied standard deviation\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2013\n)\n, i.e.,\n(5)\np\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n1\n)\n=\n𝒩\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nμ\nf\n,\nσ\n)\n,\np\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nH\n0\n)\n=\n𝒩\n​\n(\ns\ni\n|\nμ\nr\n,\nσ\n)\n,\np(s_{i}|H_{1})=\\mathcal{N}(s_{i}|\\mu_{f},\\sigma),\\quad p(s_{i}|H_{0})=\\mathcal{N}(s_{i}|\\mu_{r},\\sigma),\nwhere the learnable parameters are\nθ\n1\n=\n{\nμ\nf\n,\nσ\n}\n\\theta_{1}=\\{\\mu_{f},\\sigma\\}\nand\nθ\n0\n=\n{\nμ\nr\n,\nσ\n}\n\\theta_{0}=\\{\\mu_{r},\\sigma\\}\n.\nUnder this assumption, the resulting calibration reduces to an affine transformation\n𝒞\n​\n(\ns\ni\n)\n=\na\n​\ns\ni\n+\nb\n\\mathcal{C}(s_{i})=as_{i}+b\n, where\n(6)\na\n=\nμ\nf\n−\nμ\nr\nσ\n2\n,\nb\n=\n−\na\n​\n(\nμ\nf\n+\nμ\nr\n)\n2\n.\na=\\frac{\\mu_{\\text{f}}-\\mu_{\\text{r}}}{\\sigma^{2}},\\quad b=-\\frac{a(\\mu_{\\text{f}}+\\mu_{\\text{r}})}{2}.\nThis method is known as the constrained, maximum-likelihood, Gaussian (CMLG) calibration\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2013\n)\n.\nIn this work, we experiment with KDE and CMLG-based approaches.\nNote that each method requires a calibration set that is as representative as possible of the target (test) distribution, so that the estimated densities and resulting\nLLRs\nare meaningful.\nIf this set is not representative, the learned densities may be mismatched, leading to unreliable\nLLRs\n.\nThe choice of the calibration set is described in §\n4\n.\n2.4.\nEnsemble Aggregation Strategy\nOnce the\nLLRs\nare obtained, the straightforward approach is to sum them, motivated by the independent additivity of\nLLRs\n(Eq. (\n4\n)).\nWe also consider two alternative strategies.\nThe first uses a max operator\n(7)\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\nmax\ni\n⁡\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})=\\max_{i}\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),\nwhich retains only the strongest expert response for each sample and assumes that a single artifact may be sufficient for detection.\nThe second follows a Mixture-of-Experts formulation\n(Negroni\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\nand applies a learned gating mechanism\n(8)\nℓ\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n=\n∑\ni\nw\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n​\nℓ\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n,\n\\ell(\\mathbf{x})=\\sum_{i}w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\ell_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),\nwhere sample-dependent weights\nw\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n{w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})}\nadaptively combine expert\nLLRs\nby emphasizing the most relevant ones.\nIn practice, the calibrated per-expert scores are passed to a linear gating network with dimension equal to the number of experts, which outputs softmax-normalized weights\n{\nw\ni\n​\n(\n𝐱\n)\n}\n\\{w_{i}(\\mathbf{x})\\}\n.\nTable 1\n.\nFive artifacts investigated in this study. Abbreviations are defined for statistical parametric speech synthesis (SPSS) and line spectral frequency (LSF). Numbers in brackets for MLP-based expert architectures denote layer sizes.\nArtifact\nExample of target algorithm or module\nRaw features\nExpert input (#. proxy features)\nManipulation\nExpert Architecture\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ninconsistencies\nUnit selection\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ntrajectory\nvariability, 1st/2nd-order dynamics, ratios (10)\nshifting, shuffling, compression\nMLP (10–32–16–1)\nOversmoothed spectra\nAcoustic models in SPSS\nLSFs\nspatial/temporal spacing dynamics, coeff. variance (13)\ngaussian smoothing\nMLP (13–32–16–1)\nDegrade phase\nVocoders w/o modeling phase\nUnwrapped phase\n-\nminimum-phase reconstruction\nLight CNN (LCNN)\nEnergy inconsistencies\nUnit selection & SPSS\nLog-power spec.\nglobal + band energy, temporal deltas, drop stats (24)\nlocal attenuations\nMLP (24–32–16–1)\nTonal artifacts\nDNN-based vocoders\nSpectral fingerprint\n-\ninject resonances\nMLP (225–128–32–1)\nFigure 3\n.\nIllustrative real (top) vs. synthetic (bottom) examples for four\nof the targeted synthesis artifacts (left to right:\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ninconsistency, oversmoothing,\nenergy inconsistency, tonal artifact).\n3.\nArtifacts and Expert Models\nThis section outlines the artifacts and implementation of expert models for speech deepfake detection, designed based on our prior knowledge of speech synthesis algorithms.\nConsidering the variety of available approaches, we limit this preliminary work to\nText to Speech (TTS)\n, the most widely used and extensively studied speech synthesis paradigm, and its generated artifacts. Specifically, we consider\n5\n5\nmajor synthesis artifacts, spanning synthesis paradigms from unit selection to statistical parametric approaches, from linear models to neural methods; their implementation and association with specific deepfake families are detailed for each expert below (summary in\nTable\n1\n).\n3.1.\nF0 Inconsistencies\nGenerating an\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ntrajectory is essential for natural-sounding speech synthesis\n(Hirschberg,\n2002\n)\n. A known artifact in unit selection TTS is\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ninconsistency\n(Bořil\net al.\n,\n2017\n)\n, perceived as prosodic jumps or discontinuities in synthetic speech. This arises from the concatenation of segmented units.\nWe extract the\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ntrajectory using\npYIN\n(Mauch and Dixon,\n2014\n)\n, and apply manipulations within voiced regions. The contour is segmented into 80–160 ms units, and segments are randomly selected with probability\np\nseg\n∈\n[\n0.4\n,\n0.7\n]\np_{\\text{seg}}\\in[0.4,0.7]\n, scaled by factors in\n[\n0.87\n,\n0.92\n]\n[0.87,0.92]\nor\n[\n1.08\n,\n1.30\n]\n[1.08,1.30]\n. Selected segments are partially shuffled with probability\np\nshuffle\n∈\n[\n0.2\n,\n0.5\n]\np_{\\text{shuffle}}\\in[0.2,0.5]\n. Alternatively, with fixed probability, the\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ncontour is compressed toward its median (strength 0.4) and locally smoothed using a three-frame average (strength 0.4), reducing pitch variability. The procedure produces trajectories with either local discontinuities or reduced dynamics. Parameter ranges were empirically set to yield perceptually plausible yet pronounced artifacts for training.\nWe aggregate\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ncontours into scalar descriptors, forming a 10-dimensional feature vector for a\nMulti-Layer Perceptron (MLP)\nclassifier. Direct use of raw\nF\n0\nF_{0}\ncontours was ineffective.\n3.2.\nOversmoothing\nIn contrast to unit selection, statistical parametric speech synthesis (SPSS) uses statistical acoustic models to generate smoothed\nF\n0\nF_{0}\nand spectral trajectories\n(Tokuda\net al.\n,\n2013\n)\n.\nHowever, the generated features are often over-smoothed, resulting in muffled synthetic speech\n(Tokuda\net al.\n,\n2013\n)\n.\nThis was a central issue when using HMM\n(Tokuda\net al.\n,\n2013\n)\nand also affects more recent DNN-based acoustic models\n(Ren\net al.\n,\n2022\n)\n. The same issue can be caused by the DSP-based vocoders. Even if the trend is to switch to DNN-based vocoders, as long as the DNN-based vocoders are trained to minimize the distance of the spectral magnitude between generated and natural speech, the mean-seeking training paradigm is known to produce blurry (or over-smoothed) speech.\nWe simulate this effect by applying a Gaussian filter to\nLine Spectral Frequencies (LSF)\nalong the temporal axis, reducing frame-to-frame variation\n(Merritt and King,\n2013\n)\n.\nThe filter standard deviation is empirically set to\n2\n2\n.\nAfter filtering,\nLSF\ncoefficients are sorted within each frame to preserve ordering constraints. This yields trajectories with reduced temporal variability, approximating oversmoothed speech.\nRaw\nLSFs\nwere ineffective for training: we aggregate frame-level features over time into a 13-dimensional vector for\nMLP\n-based classification.\n3.3.\nDegraded Phase\nPhase artifacts commonly arise in three cases: 1) when using vocoders that assume a minimum-phase when reconstructing waveforms from spectral magnitude\n(Morise\net al.\n,\n2016\n)\n, 2) when using (typically DNN-based) vocoders that do not explicitly generate the phase\n(Kong\net al.\n,\n2020\n)\n, and 3) when the DNN cannot accurately generate the phase\n(Siuzdak,\n2024\n)\n.\nWe model this via controlled lossy phase reconstruction. The waveform is converted to the\nShort-Time Fourier Transform (STFT)\ndomain, retaining magnitude while discarding phase. A minimum-phase signal is reconstructed using cepstral processing by enforcing a causal liftering constraint on the log-magnitude spectrum, followed by inverse\nSTFT\n. From the reconstructed waveform, the unwrapped phase representation is extracted and used as input to a Light CNN model\n(Wu\net al.\n,\n2018\n)\n.\n3.4.\nEnergy Inconsistencies\nThis artifact occurs in both unit selection and SPSS-based TTS systems. In unit selection, it may result from imperfect concatenation, while in SPSS it appears as overly uniform regions or abrupt transitions, including unnaturally clean silences.\nWe simulate this by selecting a short temporal region (\n6\n6\n–\n30\n30\nframes) and attenuating it by a factor drawn from\n[\n0.0\n,\n0.5\n]\n[0.0,\\sqrt{0.5}]\n, producing local energy drops. The waveform is then converted to a power spectrogram via\nSTFT\nand log-scaled. We aggregate it into\n24\n24\nscalar descriptors capturing energy statistics and temporal drops, which are input to a\nMLP\n.\n3.5.\nTonal Artifacts\nNarrowband tonal artifacts can occur in neural\nTTS\nsystems using DNN-based upsampling modules, such as transposed or subpixel convolutions\n(Pons\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nThese may introduce spectral replicas and uneven overlap, producing spurious narrowband artifacts unrelated to natural harmonics. These are referred to as tonal artifacts\n(Pons\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nWe simulate this by attenuating the waveform by\n0.05\n0.05\n, then adding\n1\n1\n–\n2\n2\nnarrowband resonances using high-Q band-pass filters (1–8 kHz,\nQ\n∈\n[\n30\n,\n80\n]\nQ\\in[30,80]\n, gains\n[\n2\n,\n5\n]\n[2,5]\n).\nA nonlinearity increases contrast, followed by normalization, yielding signals dominated by sparse spectral peaks. A spectral fingerprint is extracted following\n(Afchar\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n, producing a 1D feature emphasizing these peaks for a\nMLP\n.\nFigure\n3\nshows representative real-vs-synthetic examples for four artifacts, illustrating the features used by the corresponding experts; the degraded phase is omitted due to limited suitability for 2D visualization.\nThe five artifacts are assumed to cover many speech synthesis systems in publicly available deepfake datasets\n(Wang\net al.\n,\n2020\n; Jung\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\n.\nMany voice conversion (VC) systems relying on statistical models and vocoders, DNN-based or not, may exhibit similar artifacts. A limitation of this approach is that only artifacts known a priori can be modeled by an expert. This is further discussed in §\n6\n.\n4.\nExperimental Setup\nThis section outlines the data splits (§\n4.1\n), training protocol (§\n4.2\n), and evaluation metrics (§\n4.3\n) used in our experiments.\n4.1.\nDatasets and Partitioning Protocol\nOur training data consists entirely of real speech drawn from the training sets of ASVspoof 2019\n(Wang\net al.\n,\n2020\n)\n(clean studio recordings), ASVspoof 5\n(Wang\net al.\n,\n2026\n)\n(controlled recordings), and SpoofCeleb\n(Jung\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\n(in-the-wild speech). We trim their leading and trailing silence and apply peak normalization to avoid potential shortcut learning during training\n(Müller\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nTo keep balance, each corpus is subsampled to match the size of the smallest one.\nThe resulting subsets are split\n80\n80\n/\n20\n20\nat the speaker level into disjoint training and validation sets, and the splits are concatenated across corpora.\nEvery utterance is duplicated for each expert: one copy is kept unchanged, while the other is modified to match the target artifact.\nAfter duplication, the final dataset contains\n24 526\n24\\,526\ntraining samples and\n6242\n6242\nvalidation samples.\nFor calibration, real samples are drawn from the validation set.\nWhen paired with actual deepfake samples, these are taken either from ASVspoof 2015 (attack S3 for\nF\n0\nF_{0}\nand energy experts, S10 for the others) or from the ASVspoof 2019 training set (A01 for the tonal artifact expert, A03 for the oversmoothing and phase experts, A04 for the\nF\n0\nF_{0}\nand energy ones), with A02 excluded for redundancy but retained for testing.\nFurther details on the choice of these attacks are provided in §\n5.2\n.\nFor evaluation, real samples are taken exclusively from evaluation partitions, while\nTTS\nsamples are drawn from the development and evaluation sets for ASVspoof 2019, and from all splits for ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, which are never used for calibration.\nFor ASVspoof 5, post-processed samples are excluded, as robustness assessment falls outside the scope of this initial analysis.\nFor both ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, the number of\nTTS\nsamples per attack is clipped to the size of the least represented attack class (\n7760\n7760\nand\n7963\n7963\nsamples, respectively), which remains sufficient for meaningful evaluation while balancing class distributions.\n4.2.\nTraining Specifications\nEach expert model is trained for up to\n100\n100\nepochs with early stopping after\n20\n20\nepochs without improvement.\nThe batch size is\n128\n128\n.\nOptimization uses AdamW with an initial learning rate of\n10\n−\n3\n10^{-3}\n, reduced on plateau with patience\n10\n10\n.\nTraining uses binary cross-entropy, and selection is based on validation loss.\nPseudo-fake samples are generated on-the-fly by applying the corresponding expert’s designed manipulation, with dynamic labeling (\n0\nfor real,\n1\n1\nfor manipulated).\nFor\nMLPs\nusing scalar features, inputs are standardized using statistics computed on the training set.\nThe gating network for fusing LLRs (Eq. (\n8\n)) is trained separately for\n10\n10\nepochs under the same setup.\nIn addition to binary cross-entropy, it includes an auxiliary loss enforcing correct expert-artifact attribution, since this time each pseudo-fake contains a single uniformly sampled manipulation.\nIn terms of calibration, the Gaussian\nKDE\nuses a bandwidth of\n0.1\n0.1\n.\nFor the CMLG approach, the shared variance is experimentally set to\nσ\n=\n0.5\n\\sigma={0.5}\n.\n4.3.\nEvaluation Metrics\nWe report\nArea Under the Curve (AUC)\nand\nEqual Error Rate (EER)\nfor discriminative performance.\nAUC\nmeasures ranking quality across thresholds, while\nEER\nis the operating point where false acceptance and false rejection rates are equal. Following standard practice in speech deepfake detection, validation\nEER\nis also used for model selection.\nBoth metrics are calibration-blind and depend only on score ordering.\n4\n4\n4\nAny order-preserving transformation of scores leaves\nAUC\nand\nEER\nunchanged\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2007\n, § 3.3)\n.\nTo assess calibration quality, we additionally report\nLog-Likelihood Ratio Cost (Cllr)\n, which evaluates the quality of estimated\nLLRs\nin terms of both discrimination and calibration\n(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2007\n)\n. Lower\nCllr\nindicates better-calibrated and more informative scores, while values above\n1\n1\nindicate poor calibration and weak discrimination.\n5.\nResults\nTable 2\n.\nExperts performance on ASVspoof 2019 attacks exhibiting their target artifacts, reported as AUC (\n↑\n\\uparrow\n) and EER (\n↓\n\\downarrow\n). Experts were trained using pseudo-fake data. Data from target attacks are unseen.\nExpert\nTarget Attack\nAUC (%)\nEER (%)\nF0 Inconsistencies\nA04 (Unit selection)\n77.64\n29.38\nOversmoothing\nA03 (DNN + WORLD)\n97.64\n6.62\nDegraded Phase\nA03 (DNN + WORLD)\n98.50\n6.24\nEnergy Inconsistencies\nA04 (Unit selection)\n88.23\n22.98\nTonal artifacts\nA01 (DNN + WaveNet)\n84.77\n22.86\nExperimental results are presented in this section, including the individual evaluation of the artifact-specific experts (§\n5.1\n), the optimization of calibration data and methods for the ensemble (§\n5.2\n), a comparative analysis of LLR aggregation strategies (§\n5.3\n), and an interpretability analysis mapping expert responses to the generation attacks (§\n5.4\n).\n5.1.\nEvaluation of Individual Expert\nTo showcase the performance of the artifact-specific experts, we measure their detection results on selected deepfake attacks.\nFor each expert, we select an ASVspoof 2019 attack that is expected to exhibit the targeted artifact based on its underlying components.\nSince we are interested in its discrimination power, each experts’ output score\ns\ni\ns_{i}\nis used to compute the AUC and EER without calibration (§\n4.3\n).\nResults are reported in\nTable\n2\nalongside the corresponding synthesis architectures. All experts perform above chance level (\nAUC\n=\nEER\n=\n50\n%\n\\text{AUC}=\\text{EER}=50\\%\n), indicating that the chosen expert–artifact assignments are meaningful.\nAlthough performance remains well below state-of-the-art detectors, this is expected: each expert uses a compact model and targets a single artifact rather than exploiting all available deepfake cues.\nPlus, experts are trained only on real and pseudo-fake data, not on actual TTS-generated speech (§\n2.2\n).\n5.2.\nEvaluation of Calibrated Experts in Ensemble\nEvaluation is first conducted independently for each expert, then outputs are aligned by retaining only samples valid across all experts (discarding those with failed\nF\n0\nF_{0}\n, which is\n3.24\n3.24\n%).\nPerformance of the ensemble of experts depends on how well the experts are calibrated and the strategy to fuse the calibrated LLRs. Hence, in this section,\nwe first evaluate calibration choices in\nFigure\n4\nusing a fixed sum aggregation.\nWe then compare aggregation strategies under the selected calibration setup in the next subsection.\nThe goodness of calibration is affected by the calibration data as well as the calibration method.\nIn\nFigure\n4\n, for the two calibration methods using either CMLG or KDE (§\n2.3\n), we evaluate\n4\n4\ncalibration set compositions with different data sources:\n1) pseudo-fakes as in training; 2) ASVspoof 2015 attacks, where each expert uses only a selected attack that matches its target artifact (see §\n4.1\n); 3) ASVspoof 2019 attacks under the same expert-specific setup; and 4) a pooled ASVspoof 2019 variant, where the target attacks from all experts are merged into a shared calibration set used for every expert.\nEach calibration set is further prepared in\n5\n5\nsizes, ranging from\n10\n10\nto\n1000\n1000\nfake utterances per attack.\nThe real utterances for each set, drawn from validation set, are subsampled to be equal to the number of fake samples.\nThe evaluation set is ASVspoof 2019.\nWe observe that only the 4th choice (i.e., the pooled ASVspoof 2019 variant) yields acceptable\nCllr\nvalues (below\n1.0\n1.0\n), indicating that a shared calibration set across experts leads to a more stable ensemble, with the best results obtained using the CMLG calibration function.\nIn this condition, the number of utterances is a negligible factor; the gap between KDE and the CMLG-based calibration methods is also small.\nSpecifically, the best setup scores\n19.76\n19.76\n%\nEER\nand\n0.638\n0.638\nCllr\n, using only\n50\n50\nsamples per calibration class (i.e., each attack type).\n5.3.\nEvaluation of Experts Aggregation\nUsing the best calibration data and method identified in the previous subsection, we compared three aggregation methods (§\n2.4\n) on the ASVspoof 2019 evaluation set. The results presented in\nTable\n3\nshow that summing expert\nLLRs\nconsistently achieves the best performance in terms of both\nEER\nand Cllr, outperforming max-based and learned gating strategies (\nTable\n3\n).\nTable 3\n.\nEnsemble aggregation strategies comparison on ASVspoof 2019 evaluation set. EER (\n↓\n\\downarrow\n), Cllr (\n↓\n\\downarrow\n).\nAggregation Method\nEER (%)\nCllr\nSum of Expert LLRs\n19.76\n0.638\nMaximum Expert LLR\n22.22\n0.855\nGating Network\n21.54\n0.907\nFigure 4\n.\nEnsemble overall performance on ASVspoof 2019 for different calibration functions, calibration set compositions, and calibration set sizes:\nEER\n(left) and\nCllr\n(right).\nCllr\nvalues above 3 are clipped for visualization.\n5.4.\nInterpretability Analysis\nIn\nTable\n4(a)\n, we report the\nLLRs\nof the experts in the best-performing ensemble identified in §\n5.2\n, computed for each ASVspoof 2019 attack.\nOverall, average\nLLRs\nremain lower for real than fake samples across all experts, indicating consistent ensemble behavior.\nAlso, the expert responses are consistent with the characteristics of the underlying generation pipeline of most deepfake attacks: for example, attacks based on HMM/DNN acoustic models consistently yield positive\nLLRs\nfrom the oversmoothing expert, while attacks employing DSP-based (WORLD, Vocaine) or DNN vocoders without phase conditioning (Neural Source-Filter) systematically activate the phase expert.\nThis behavior is expected, as the experts are designed to capture specific types of artifacts, which match the generation techniques represented in the dataset used.\nMoreover, the strength of the expert responses varies considerably across attacks.\nSome attacks elicit only weak activations, whereas others trigger multiple experts simultaneously, indicating the coexistence of several artifacts within the same generation pipeline.\nIn contrast to the other experts, the\nF\n0\nF_{0}\none exhibits weaker responses across most attacks, consistent with its lower pre-calibration discriminative performance (\nTable\n2\n) and suggesting that\nF\n0\nF_{0}\n-related artifacts might be less consistently present or expressed in these attacks.\nWe then examine the performance of experts on ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, which include newer-generation attacks. As long as the artifacts persist in the newer attacks, they are expected to be spotted by the experts.\nThe calibration set is kept unchanged from the ASVspoof 2019 setup.\nOn ASVspoof 5 (\nTable\n5\n), oversmoothing and degraded phase remain consistently activated across many attacks, suggesting partial persistence of these artifacts in newer\nTTS\nsystems.\nIn contrast, energy inconsistencies largely disappear, with only a few isolated exceptions (Tacotron2+WaveGrad exhibits unnaturally blank silences).\nA similar pattern holds for tonal artifacts, which remain active only for specific systems and partially overlap with those triggering the energy expert, with responses concentrated mainly on Toucan TTS-based attacks across different vocoders.\nSpoofCeleb (\nTable\n6\n) is overall more challenging but also shows promising results.\nOversmoothing and degraded phase remain the most prominent artifacts, while energy inconsistencies almost vanish.\nThe tonal expert responds strongly only to WaveGlow-based systems, consistent with their characteristic audible distortions.\nNotably, real samples are not always assigned negative\nLLRs\nacross experts, suggesting artifact-like characteristics in in-the-wild recordings.\nWhile not desirable, this is not unexpected, as expert outputs represent evidence of specific artifacts rather than global authenticity.\nGlobal decisions are instead obtained by aggregating these signals at the ensemble level into\nH\n0\nH_{0}\n(real) and\nH\n1\nH_{1}\n(fake), which is meant to help mitigate inconsistencies across individual experts.\nOverall, the interpretability analysis shows that the artifact-specific experts yield expected results on ASVspoof 2019 by producing positive LLRs to their targeted synthesis pipelines. Furthermore, evaluation on newer datasets demonstrates that these experts also generalize well to varied extents, catching persistent acoustic and phase distortions in modern architectures.\nTable 4\n.\nExpert\nLLRs\non ASVspoof 2019. Higher values indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\nH\n1\nH_{1}\n).\nBold\nvalues indicate positive\nLLRs\n.\n(a)\nArtifact-specific experts reporting calibrated LLRs per attack. The first three attacks are included in each expert’s calibration set.\nAvg Real\nHMM/DNN\nWaveNet\nDNN\nWORLD\nUnit Selection\nHMM/DNN\nWORLD\nDNN\nWORLD+GAN\nHMM/DNN\nNeural SF\nDNN\nVocaine\nTacotron2\nWaveRNN\nTacotron2\nGriffin-Lim\nDNN\nWaveNet\nAvg Fake\nF0 Inconsistencies\n0.00\n-0.01\n0.02\n-0.02\n0.03\n0.03\n0.00\n0.03\n0.00\n0.01\n0.00\n0.01\nOversmoothing\n-0.10\n0.05\n0.30\n-0.20\n0.19\n-0.18\n0.13\n0.24\n-0.16\n0.08\n-0.25\n0.02\nDegraded Phase\n-0.39\n0.04\n0.71\n-0.37\n-0.17\n0.27\n0.61\n1.03\n0.06\n0.20\n-0.10\n0.23\nEnergy Inconsistencies\n-0.49\n-0.77\n0.63\n1.77\n-0.44\n-0.32\n0.01\n1.25\n-0.28\n1.52\n2.09\n0.55\nTonal Artifacts\n-0.09\n0.60\n0.31\n-0.08\n0.17\n0.06\n0.44\n0.04\n-0.10\n-0.05\n-0.11\n0.13\n(b)\nAdditional silence duration expert reporting per-attack calibrated LLRs. The first three attacks are part of its calibration set.\nAvg Real\nHMM/DNN\nWaveNet\nDNN\nWORLD\nUnit Selection\nHMM/DNN\nWORLD\nDNN\nWORLD+GAN\nHMM/DNN\nNeural SF\nDNN\nVocaine\nTacotron2\nWaveRNN\nTacotron2\nGriffin-Lim\nDNN\nWaveNet\nAvg Fake\nSilence Duration Bias\n-0.19\n0.48\n-0.08\n0.30\n-0.13\n1.88\n-0.03\n0.91\n2.27\n2.05\n0.59\n0.82\nTable 5\n.\nExpert\nLLRs\non ASVspoof 5, reported per attack. Top: acoustic model; bottom: vocoder or no distinction. Higher LLRs indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\nH\n1\nH_{1}\n).\nBold\nvalues indicate positive LLRs.\nAvg Real\nGlowTTS\nHiFiGAN\nGradTTS\nHiFiGAN\nVAE\nHiFiGAN\nXTTS\nHiFiGAN\nVITS\nHiFiGAN\nYourTTS\nYourTTS v2\nFastPitch\nHiFiGAN\nToucan TTS\nHiFiGAN\nToucan TTS\nHiFiGAN v2\nToucan TTS\nBigVGAN\nToucan TTS\nBigVGAN v2\nTacotron2\nWaveGrad\nUnit Sel.\nUnit Sel.\nAvg Fake\nF0 Inconsistencies\n-0.01\n0.00\n0.00\n0.01\n0.01\n0.02\n-0.01\n0.01\n0.02\n0.02\n0.02\n0.02\n0.01\n0.01\n-0.02\n0.01\n0.01\nOversmoothing\n-0.16\n0.30\n0.24\n0.11\n0.18\n0.21\n0.08\n0.06\n0.46\n0.23\n0.23\n0.30\n0.20\n0.13\n-0.33\n0.04\n0.15\nDegraded Phase\n-0.14\n0.17\n0.24\n0.06\n0.30\n0.05\n0.23\n0.18\n0.35\n0.26\n0.26\n0.17\n0.29\n0.03\n-0.36\n0.06\n0.14\nEnergy Inconsist.\n-0.25\n-0.75\n-0.70\n-0.57\n-0.57\n-0.77\n-0.89\n-0.41\n-0.81\n0.14\n0.15\n0.12\n0.61\n2.06\n-0.17\n-0.57\n-0.19\nTonal Artifacts\n-0.13\n-0.22\n-0.28\n-0.18\n-0.24\n-0.13\n-0.35\n-0.13\n-0.29\n0.17\n0.16\n0.01\n0.18\n-0.10\n-0.13\n-0.06\n-0.11\nTable 6\n.\nExpert\nLLRs\non SpoofCeleb, reported per attack. Top: acoustic model; bottom: vocoder or no distinction. Higher LLRs indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\nH\n1\nH_{1}\n).\nBold\nvalues indicate positive LLRs.\nAvg Real\nVITS\nMQTTS\nVALL-E\nDelay\nGradTTS\nDiffWave\nMatchaTTS\nDiffWave\nGradTTS\nBigVGAN\nMatchaTTS\nBigVGAN\nGradTTS\nWaveGlow\nMatchaTTS\nWaveGlow\nGradTTS\nNSF HiFiGAN\nMatchaTTS\nNSF HiFiGAN\nBVAE-TTS\nNSF HiFiGAN\nGradTTS\nHiFiGAN\nMatchaTTS\nHiFiGAN\nBVAE-TTS\nHiFiGAN\nMS-Transf\nTransfTTS\nPWG\nAvg Fake\nF0 Inconsistencies\n0.01\n0.00\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.00\n0.01\n0.00\n0.01\n-0.02\n-0.02\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\n0.01\nOversmoothing\n0.31\n0.14\n0.25\n0.24\n0.22\n0.05\n0.16\n0.22\n0.26\n-0.04\n0.29\n0.33\n0.32\n0.30\n0.33\n0.33\n0.35\n0.31\n0.32\n0.24\nDegraded Phase\n-0.06\n0.24\n0.25\n0.07\n0.32\n0.00\n0.24\n-0.22\n0.05\n-0.05\n-0.13\n0.44\n-0.06\n-0.20\n-0.06\n0.42\n-0.03\n-0.05\n-0.05\n0.07\nEnergy Inconsist.\n-1.10\n-0.74\n-0.41\n-0.86\n-0.79\n-1.16\n-0.98\n-0.97\n-0.86\n-1.03\n-0.95\n-0.94\n-1.10\n-1.09\n-1.10\n-0.94\n-1.10\n-1.10\n-1.10\n-0.96\nTonal Artifacts\n-0.36\n0.18\n-0.08\n-0.08\n-0.01\n0.08\n0.10\n-0.01\n-0.05\n3.01\n3.02\n-0.11\n-0.36\n-0.35\n-0.35\n-0.10\n-0.34\n-0.36\n-0.35\n0.21\n5.5.\nInterpretability for Shortcut Diagnosis\nAll experts in this work operate on features treated as nuisance-robust representations and are not intended to exploit any dataset-specific shortcuts\n(Sahidullah\net al.\n,\n2025\n)\n, but we can add experts to diagnose potential shortcuts.\nThe impact of a shortcut can be revealed by comparing 1) the values of calibrated\nLLRs\nfrom the suspected expert with others and 2) the ensemble’s performance with and without the suspected expert. The latter can be easily done since the framework is inherently modular: expert outputs are combined as a linear sum, and an expert can be directly added to or removed from the ensemble. No modification or retraining is required for other experts.\nAs a demonstration, we introduce a 6th control expert targeting a known dataset bias related to silence-duration patterns\n(Müller\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nSilence intervals are extracted by applying a voice activity detector and deriving complementary non-speech regions.\nTo generate pseudofakes, the silence-duration sequence is stochastically compressed toward its mean, perturbed with controlled noise, truncated for overly long pauses, and constrained at sequence boundaries.\nThis reflects the tendency of synthetic speech to exhibit reduced variability and shorter silences, particularly at leading and trailing positions\n(Müller\net al.\n,\n2021\n)\n.\nFeatures are summarized into\n10\n10\nproxies and classified using a dedicated MLP (10–32–16–1).\nThis expert is designed, trained, and calibrated independently from the others.\nIts calibration set differs slightly from those of the other experts, as real samples are drawn exclusively from ASVspoof 2019 due to the dataset-dependent nature of the targeted artifact.\nResults on ASVspoof 2019\nTTS\nattacks in\nTable\n4(b)\nshow expected traits of shortcut: particularly for Tacotron2 + WaveRNN, where previous experts were weak, the added expert provides very strong ‘evidence’ (\nLLR\n¿\n2\n2\n). At the ensemble level, the expert reduced the EER to around 12%. However, since the expert only relies on silence duration, the large magnitude of\nLLR\nand reduced EER suggest that the expert is exploiting the dataset-specific shortcut.\nWe show the new ensemble performance in\nFigure\n5\n, along with the confusion matrix at threshold\n0\n.\nFigure 5\n.\nEnsemble overall performance on ASVspoof 2019 after adding the sixth expert. ROC curve and confusion matrix (LLR scores threshold set at 0).\n6.\nConclusions\nWe proposed an interpretable speech deepfake detection framework based on artifact-specific expert models. The system decomposes detection into learning and recognition of predefined synthesis artifacts, each modeled by a dedicated classifier trained on pseudo-fake data.\nExpert outputs are calibrated into\nLLRs\n, providing a common interpretable measure of evidence linking decisions to artifact presence.\nExperiments show that (i) experts reliably detect their target artifacts, (ii) calibration is essential for meaningful comparison across experts, and (iii)\nLLR\nsummation is the most effective aggregation strategy.\nThe framework provides an interpretable mechanism for identifying synthesis artifacts while maintaining a modular architecture that can be extended as new artifact classes emerge. It also helps to diagnose potential dataset shortcuts.\nFuture work will focus on broadening the range of artifact-specific experts to capture the increasingly diverse characteristics of modern speech synthesis systems. Adapting automated rule-learning frameworks from the visual domain\n(Raza\net al.\n,\n2024\n)\nto extract and compose speech anomalies into human-interpretable artifacts represents a promising direction for long-term, extendable development.\nOther topics, such as improved calibration and refined expert pipelines, are also expected to further boost the overall performance.\nOwing to its additive and modular design, these developments can be incorporated by introducing new experts while preserving the interpretability and extensibility of the overall framework.\nReferences\nD. Afchar, G. Meseguer-Brocal, K. Akesbi, and R. Hennequin (2025)\nA Fourier explanation of AI-music artifacts\n.\nIn\nProceedings of the International Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR)\n,\nCited by:\n§3.5\n.\nF. Alonso-Fernandez, K. B. Raja, R. Raghavendra, C. Busch, J. Bigun, R. Vera-Rodriguez, and J. Fierrez (2022)\nCross-sensor periocular biometrics in a global pandemic: Comparative benchmark and novel multialgorithmic approach\n.\nInformation Fusion\n83-84\n,\npp. 110–130\n.\nCited by:\n§2.1\n.\nA. Bassit, F. Hahn, J. Peeters, T. Kevenaar, R. Veldhuis, and A. Peter (2021)\nFast and accurate likelihood ratio-based biometric verification secure against malicious adversaries\n.\nIEEE Transactions on Information Forensics and Security\n16\n,\npp. 5045–5060\n.\nExternal Links:\nISSN 1556-6013, 1556-6021\nCited by:\n§2.1\n.\nI. Ben-Amor, J. Bonastre, B. O’Brien, and P. Bousquet (2023)\nDescribing the phonetics in the underlying speech attributes for deep and interpretable speaker recognition\n.\nIn\nProc. Interspeech 2023\n,\npp. 3207–3211\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n,\nfootnote 1\n.\nT. Bořil, P. Šturm, R. Skarnitzl, and J. Volín (2017)\nEffect of formant and F0 discontinuity on perceived vowel duration: Impacts for concatenative speech synthesis\n.\nIn\nProc. Interspeech 2017\n,\npp. 2998–3002\n.\nCited by:\n§3.1\n.\nC. Borrelli, P. Bestagini, F. Antonacci, A. Sarti, and S. Tubaro (2021)\nSynthetic speech detection through short-term and long-term prediction traces\n.\nEURASIP Journal on Information Security\n2021\n(\n1\n),\npp. 2\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nN. Brummer, A. Swart, and D. V. Leeuwen (2014)\nA comparison of linear and non-linear calibrations for speaker recognition\n.\nIn\nThe Speaker and Language Recognition Workshop (Odyssey 2014)\n,\npp. 14–18\n.\nCited by:\n§2.3.2\n.\nC. Champod, A. Biedermann, J. Vuille, S. Willis, and J. De Kinder (2016)\nENFSI guideline for evaluative reporting in forensic science: a primer for legal practitioners\n.\nCriminal Law and Justice Weekly\n180\n(\n10\n),\npp. 189–193\n.\nCited by:\nfootnote 3\n.\nL. Cuccovillo, P. Aichroth, and T. Köllmer (2023)\nCalibrating neural networks for synthetic speech detection: a likelihood-ratio-based approach\n.\nIn\nAudio Engineering Society (AES) International Conference on Audio Forensics\n,\nCited by:\n§2.3.2\n.\nW. Ge, M. Todisco, and N. Evans (2022)\nExplainable deepfake and spoofing detection: an attack analysis using shapley additive explanations\n.\nIn\nThe Speaker and Language Recognition Workshop (Odyssey 2022)\n,\npp. 70–76\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nW. Ge, X. Wang, X. Liu, and J. Yamagishi (2025)\nPost-training for deepfake speech detection\n.\nIn\nIEEE Automatic Speech Recognition and Understanding Workshop (ASRU)\n,\npp. 1–8\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nH. Gu, J. Yi, C. Wang, J. Tao, Z. Lian, J. He, Y. Ren, Y. Chen, and Z. Wen (2025)\nALLM4ADD: unlocking the capabilities of audio large language models for audio deepfake detection\n.\nIn\nProceedings of the 33rd ACM International Conference on Multimedia\n,\npp. 11736–11745\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nJ. Hirschberg (2002)\nCommunication and prosody: functional aspects of prosody\n.\nSpeech Communication\n36\n(\n1–2\n),\npp. 31–43\n.\nCited by:\n§3.1\n.\nW. Huang, Y. Gu, Z. Wang, H. Zhu, and Y. Qian (2025)\nSpeechFake: A large-scale multilingual speech deepfake dataset toward cutting-edge speech generation methods\n.\nIn\nProceedings of the 63rd Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics\n,\npp. 9985–9998\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nE. T. Jaynes (2003)\nProbability theory: The logic of science\n.\nCambridge university press\n.\nCited by:\n§2.1\n.\nJ. Jung, H. Heo, H. Tak, H. Shim, J. S. Chung, B. Lee, H. Yu, and N. Evans (2022)\nAASIST: audio anti-spoofing using integrated spectro-temporal graph attention networks\n.\nIn\nIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP)\n,\npp. 6367–6371\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nJ. Jung, Y. Wu, X. Wang, J. Kim, S. Maiti, Y. Matsunaga, H. Shim, J. Tian, N. Evans, J. S. Chung,\net al.\n(2024)\nSpoofCeleb: speech deepfake detection and sasv in the wild\n.\nIEEE Open Journal of Signal Processing\n6\n,\npp. 68–77\n.\nCited by:\n§3.5\n,\n§4.1\n.\nJ. Kong, J. Kim, and J. Bae (2020)\nHiFi-GAN: generative adversarial networks for efficient and high fidelity speech synthesis\n.\nIn\nProc. NIPS\n,\nVol.\n33\n,\npp. 17022–17033\n.\nCited by:\n§3.3\n.\nC. L. Machado, X. Wang, and J. Yamagishi (2025)\nTowards a transparent and interpretable strategy for spoofed speech detection\n.\nIn\nThe 33rd Annual Conference of the International Association for Forensic Phonetics and Acoustics (IAFPA)\n,\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nM. Mandasari (2018)\nSpeaker recognition system in forensic conditions: The calibration and evaluation of the likelihood ratio\n.\nphd\n,\nRadboud University\n.\nCited by:\n§2.3.1\n.\nM. Mauch and S. Dixon (2014)\npYIN: A fundamental frequency estimator using probabilistic threshold distributions\n.\nIn\nIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP)\n,\npp. 659–663\n.\nCited by:\n§3.1\n.\nT. Merritt and S. King (2013)\nInvestigating the shortcomings of hmm synthesis\n.\nIn\nProceedings of 8th ISCA Speech Synthesis Workshop\n,\npp. 185–190\n.\nCited by:\n§3.2\n.\nJ. Mishra, M. Chhibber, H. Shim, and T. H. Kinnunen (2026)\nTowards explainable spoofed speech attribution and detection: a probabilistic approach for characterizing speech synthesizer components\n.\nComputer Speech & Language\n95\n,\npp. 101840\n.\n", "numLines": 3001, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 3001}}}
