{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a7e7d281511232ff", "type": "tool_result", "content": "2000\t.\n2001\tTo assess calibration quality, we additionally report\n2002\tLog-Likelihood Ratio Cost (Cllr)\n2003\t, which evaluates the quality of estimated\n2004\tLLRs\n2005\tin terms of both discrimination and calibration\n2006\t(van Leeuwen and Brümmer,\n2007\t2007\n2008\t)\n2009\t. Lower\n2010\tCllr\n2011\tindicates better-calibrated and more informative scores, while values above\n2012\t1\n2013\t1\n2014\tindicate poor calibration and weak discrimination.\n2015\t5.\n2016\tResults\n2017\tTable 2\n2018\t.\n2019\tExperts performance on ASVspoof 2019 attacks exhibiting their target artifacts, reported as AUC (\n2020\t↑\n2021\t\\uparrow\n2022\t) and EER (\n2023\t↓\n2024\t\\downarrow\n2025\t). Experts were trained using pseudo-fake data. Data from target attacks are unseen.\n2026\tExpert\n2027\tTarget Attack\n2028\tAUC (%)\n2029\tEER (%)\n2030\tF0 Inconsistencies\n2031\tA04 (Unit selection)\n2032\t77.64\n2033\t29.38\n2034\tOversmoothing\n2035\tA03 (DNN + WORLD)\n2036\t97.64\n2037\t6.62\n2038\tDegraded Phase\n2039\tA03 (DNN + WORLD)\n2040\t98.50\n2041\t6.24\n2042\tEnergy Inconsistencies\n2043\tA04 (Unit selection)\n2044\t88.23\n2045\t22.98\n2046\tTonal artifacts\n2047\tA01 (DNN + WaveNet)\n2048\t84.77\n2049\t22.86\n2050\tExperimental results are presented in this section, including the individual evaluation of the artifact-specific experts (§\n2051\t5.1\n2052\t), the optimization of calibration data and methods for the ensemble (§\n2053\t5.2\n2054\t), a comparative analysis of LLR aggregation strategies (§\n2055\t5.3\n2056\t), and an interpretability analysis mapping expert responses to the generation attacks (§\n2057\t5.4\n2058\t).\n2059\t5.1.\n2060\tEvaluation of Individual Expert\n2061\tTo showcase the performance of the artifact-specific experts, we measure their detection results on selected deepfake attacks.\n2062\tFor each expert, we select an ASVspoof 2019 attack that is expected to exhibit the targeted artifact based on its underlying components.\n2063\tSince we are interested in its discrimination power, each experts’ output score\n2064\ts\n2065\ti\n2066\ts_{i}\n2067\tis used to compute the AUC and EER without calibration (§\n2068\t4.3\n2069\t).\n2070\tResults are reported in\n2071\tTable\n2072\t2\n2073\talongside the corresponding synthesis architectures. All experts perform above chance level (\n2074\tAUC\n2075\t=\n2076\tEER\n2077\t=\n2078\t50\n2079\t%\n2080\t\\text{AUC}=\\text{EER}=50\\%\n2081\t), indicating that the chosen expert–artifact assignments are meaningful.\n2082\tAlthough performance remains well below state-of-the-art detectors, this is expected: each expert uses a compact model and targets a single artifact rather than exploiting all available deepfake cues.\n2083\tPlus, experts are trained only on real and pseudo-fake data, not on actual TTS-generated speech (§\n2084\t2.2\n2085\t).\n2086\t5.2.\n2087\tEvaluation of Calibrated Experts in Ensemble\n2088\tEvaluation is first conducted independently for each expert, then outputs are aligned by retaining only samples valid across all experts (discarding those with failed\n2089\tF\n2090\t0\n2091\tF_{0}\n2092\t, which is\n2093\t3.24\n2094\t3.24\n2095\t%).\n2096\tPerformance of the ensemble of experts depends on how well the experts are calibrated and the strategy to fuse the calibrated LLRs. Hence, in this section,\n2097\twe first evaluate calibration choices in\n2098\tFigure\n2099\t4\n2100\tusing a fixed sum aggregation.\n2101\tWe then compare aggregation strategies under the selected calibration setup in the next subsection.\n2102\tThe goodness of calibration is affected by the calibration data as well as the calibration method.\n2103\tIn\n2104\tFigure\n2105\t4\n2106\t, for the two calibration methods using either CMLG or KDE (§\n2107\t2.3\n2108\t), we evaluate\n2109\t4\n2110\t4\n2111\tcalibration set compositions with different data sources:\n2112\t1) pseudo-fakes as in training; 2) ASVspoof 2015 attacks, where each expert uses only a selected attack that matches its target artifact (see §\n2113\t4.1\n2114\t); 3) ASVspoof 2019 attacks under the same expert-specific setup; and 4) a pooled ASVspoof 2019 variant, where the target attacks from all experts are merged into a shared calibration set used for every expert.\n2115\tEach calibration set is further prepared in\n2116\t5\n2117\t5\n2118\tsizes, ranging from\n2119\t10\n2120\t10\n2121\tto\n2122\t1000\n2123\t1000\n2124\tfake utterances per attack.\n2125\tThe real utterances for each set, drawn from validation set, are subsampled to be equal to the number of fake samples.\n2126\tThe evaluation set is ASVspoof 2019.\n2127\tWe observe that only the 4th choice (i.e., the pooled ASVspoof 2019 variant) yields acceptable\n2128\tCllr\n2129\tvalues (below\n2130\t1.0\n2131\t1.0\n2132\t), indicating that a shared calibration set across experts leads to a more stable ensemble, with the best results obtained using the CMLG calibration function.\n2133\tIn this condition, the number of utterances is a negligible factor; the gap between KDE and the CMLG-based calibration methods is also small.\n2134\tSpecifically, the best setup scores\n2135\t19.76\n2136\t19.76\n2137\t%\n2138\tEER\n2139\tand\n2140\t0.638\n2141\t0.638\n2142\tCllr\n2143\t, using only\n2144\t50\n2145\t50\n2146\tsamples per calibration class (i.e., each attack type).\n2147\t5.3.\n2148\tEvaluation of Experts Aggregation\n2149\tUsing the best calibration data and method identified in the previous subsection, we compared three aggregation methods (§\n2150\t2.4\n2151\t) on the ASVspoof 2019 evaluation set. The results presented in\n2152\tTable\n2153\t3\n2154\tshow that summing expert\n2155\tLLRs\n2156\tconsistently achieves the best performance in terms of both\n2157\tEER\n2158\tand Cllr, outperforming max-based and learned gating strategies (\n2159\tTable\n2160\t3\n2161\t).\n2162\tTable 3\n2163\t.\n2164\tEnsemble aggregation strategies comparison on ASVspoof 2019 evaluation set. EER (\n2165\t↓\n2166\t\\downarrow\n2167\t), Cllr (\n2168\t↓\n2169\t\\downarrow\n2170\t).\n2171\tAggregation Method\n2172\tEER (%)\n2173\tCllr\n2174\tSum of Expert LLRs\n2175\t19.76\n2176\t0.638\n2177\tMaximum Expert LLR\n2178\t22.22\n2179\t0.855\n2180\tGating Network\n2181\t21.54\n2182\t0.907\n2183\tFigure 4\n2184\t.\n2185\tEnsemble overall performance on ASVspoof 2019 for different calibration functions, calibration set compositions, and calibration set sizes:\n2186\tEER\n2187\t(left) and\n2188\tCllr\n2189\t(right).\n2190\tCllr\n2191\tvalues above 3 are clipped for visualization.\n2192\t5.4.\n2193\tInterpretability Analysis\n2194\tIn\n2195\tTable\n2196\t4(a)\n2197\t, we report the\n2198\tLLRs\n2199\tof the experts in the best-performing ensemble identified in §\n2200\t5.2\n2201\t, computed for each ASVspoof 2019 attack.\n2202\tOverall, average\n2203\tLLRs\n2204\tremain lower for real than fake samples across all experts, indicating consistent ensemble behavior.\n2205\tAlso, the expert responses are consistent with the characteristics of the underlying generation pipeline of most deepfake attacks: for example, attacks based on HMM/DNN acoustic models consistently yield positive\n2206\tLLRs\n2207\tfrom the oversmoothing expert, while attacks employing DSP-based (WORLD, Vocaine) or DNN vocoders without phase conditioning (Neural Source-Filter) systematically activate the phase expert.\n2208\tThis behavior is expected, as the experts are designed to capture specific types of artifacts, which match the generation techniques represented in the dataset used.\n2209\tMoreover, the strength of the expert responses varies considerably across attacks.\n2210\tSome attacks elicit only weak activations, whereas others trigger multiple experts simultaneously, indicating the coexistence of several artifacts within the same generation pipeline.\n2211\tIn contrast to the other experts, the\n2212\tF\n2213\t0\n2214\tF_{0}\n2215\tone exhibits weaker responses across most attacks, consistent with its lower pre-calibration discriminative performance (\n2216\tTable\n2217\t2\n2218\t) and suggesting that\n2219\tF\n2220\t0\n2221\tF_{0}\n2222\t-related artifacts might be less consistently present or expressed in these attacks.\n2223\tWe then examine the performance of experts on ASVspoof 5 and SpoofCeleb, which include newer-generation attacks. As long as the artifacts persist in the newer attacks, they are expected to be spotted by the experts.\n2224\tThe calibration set is kept unchanged from the ASVspoof 2019 setup.\n2225\tOn ASVspoof 5 (\n2226\tTable\n2227\t5\n2228\t), oversmoothing and degraded phase remain consistently activated across many attacks, suggesting partial persistence of these artifacts in newer\n2229\tTTS\n2230\tsystems.\n2231\tIn contrast, energy inconsistencies largely disappear, with only a few isolated exceptions (Tacotron2+WaveGrad exhibits unnaturally blank silences).\n2232\tA similar pattern holds for tonal artifacts, which remain active only for specific systems and partially overlap with those triggering the energy expert, with responses concentrated mainly on Toucan TTS-based attacks across different vocoders.\n2233\tSpoofCeleb (\n2234\tTable\n2235\t6\n2236\t) is overall more challenging but also shows promising results.\n2237\tOversmoothing and degraded phase remain the most prominent artifacts, while energy inconsistencies almost vanish.\n2238\tThe tonal expert responds strongly only to WaveGlow-based systems, consistent with their characteristic audible distortions.\n2239\tNotably, real samples are not always assigned negative\n2240\tLLRs\n2241\tacross experts, suggesting artifact-like characteristics in in-the-wild recordings.\n2242\tWhile not desirable, this is not unexpected, as expert outputs represent evidence of specific artifacts rather than global authenticity.\n2243\tGlobal decisions are instead obtained by aggregating these signals at the ensemble level into\n2244\tH\n2245\t0\n2246\tH_{0}\n2247\t(real) and\n2248\tH\n2249\t1\n2250\tH_{1}\n2251\t(fake), which is meant to help mitigate inconsistencies across individual experts.\n2252\tOverall, the interpretability analysis shows that the artifact-specific experts yield expected results on ASVspoof 2019 by producing positive LLRs to their targeted synthesis pipelines. Furthermore, evaluation on newer datasets demonstrates that these experts also generalize well to varied extents, catching persistent acoustic and phase distortions in modern architectures.\n2253\tTable 4\n2254\t.\n2255\tExpert\n2256\tLLRs\n2257\ton ASVspoof 2019. Higher values indicate stronger evidence in favor of the fake hypothesis (\n2258\tH\n2259\t1\n2260\tH_{1}\n2261\t).\n2262\tBold\n2263\tvalues indicate positive\n2264\tLLRs\n2265\t.\n2266\t(a)\n2267\tArtifact-specific experts reporting calibrated LLRs per attack. The first three attacks are included in each expert’s calibration set.\n2268\tAvg Real\n2269\tHMM/DNN\n2270\tWaveNet\n2271\tDNN\n2272\tWORLD\n2273\tUnit Selection\n2274\tHMM/DNN\n2275\tWORLD\n2276\tDNN\n2277\tWORLD+GAN\n2278\tHMM/DNN\n2279\tNeural SF\n2280\tDNN\n2281\tVocaine\n2282\tTacotron2\n2283\tWaveRNN\n2284\tTacotron2\n2285\tGriffin-Lim\n2286\tDNN\n2287\tWaveNet\n2288\tAvg Fake\n2289\tF0 Inconsistencies\n2290\t0.00\n2291\t-0.01\n2292\t0.02\n2293\t-0.02\n2294\t0.03\n2295\t0.03\n2296\t0.00\n2297\t0.03\n2298\t0.00\n2299\t0.01\n2300\t0.00\n2301\t0.01\n2302\tOversmoothing\n2303\t-0.10\n2304\t0.05\n2305\t0.30\n2306\t-0.20\n2307\t0.19\n2308\t-0.18\n2309\t0.13\n2310\t0.24\n2311\t-0.16\n2312\t0.08\n2313\t-0.25\n2314\t0.02\n2315\tDegraded Phase\n2316\t-0.39\n2317\t0.04\n2318\t0.71\n2319\t-0.37\n2320\t-0.17\n2321\t0.27\n2322\t0.61\n2323\t1.03\n2324\t0.06\n2325\t0.20\n2326\t-0.10\n2327\t0.23\n2328\tEnergy Inconsistencies\n2329\t-0.49\n2330\t-0.77\n2331\t0.63\n2332\t1.77\n2333\t-0.44\n2334\t-0.32\n2335\t0.01\n2336\t1.25\n2337\t-0.28\n2338\t1.52\n2339\t2.09\n2