2596\t0.33\n2597\t0.32\n2598\t0.30\n2599\t0.33\n2600\t0.33\n2601\t0.35\n2602\t0.31\n2603\t0.32\n2604\t0.24\n2605\tDegraded Phase\n2606\t-0.06\n2607\t0.24\n2608\t0.25\n2609\t0.07\n2610\t0.32\n2611\t0.00\n2612\t0.24\n2613\t-0.22\n2614\t0.05\n2615\t-0.05\n2616\t-0.13\n2617\t0.44\n2618\t-0.06\n2619\t-0.20\n2620\t-0.06\n2621\t0.42\n2622\t-0.03\n2623\t-0.05\n2624\t-0.05\n2625\t0.07\n2626\tEnergy Inconsist.\n2627\t-1.10\n2628\t-0.74\n2629\t-0.41\n2630\t-0.86\n2631\t-0.79\n2632\t-1.16\n2633\t-0.98\n2634\t-0.97\n2635\t-0.86\n2636\t-1.03\n2637\t-0.95\n2638\t-0.94\n2639\t-1.10\n2640\t-1.09\n2641\t-1.10\n2642\t-0.94\n2643\t-1.10\n2644\t-1.10\n2645\t-1.10\n2646\t-0.96\n2647\tTonal Artifacts\n2648\t-0.36\n2649\t0.18\n2650\t-0.08\n2651\t-0.08\n2652\t-0.01\n2653\t0.08\n2654\t0.10\n2655\t-0.01\n2656\t-0.05\n2657\t3.01\n2658\t3.02\n2659\t-0.11\n2660\t-0.36\n2661\t-0.35\n2662\t-0.35\n2663\t-0.10\n2664\t-0.34\n2665\t-0.36\n2666\t-0.35\n2667\t0.21\n2668\t5.5.\n2669\tInterpretability for Shortcut Diagnosis\n2670\tAll experts in this work operate on features treated as nuisance-robust representations and are not intended to exploit any dataset-specific shortcuts\n2671\t(Sahidullah\n2672\tet al.\n2673\t,\n2674\t2025\n2675\t)\n2676\t, but we can add experts to diagnose potential shortcuts.\n2677\tThe impact of a shortcut can be revealed by comparing 1) the values of calibrated\n2678\tLLRs\n2679\tfrom the suspected expert with others and 2) the ensemble’s performance with and without the suspected expert. The latter can be easily done since the framework is inherently modular: expert outputs are combined as a linear sum, and an expert can be directly added to or removed from the ensemble. No modification or retraining is required for other experts.\n2680\tAs a demonstration, we introduce a 6th control expert targeting a known dataset bias related to silence-duration patterns\n2681\t(Müller\n2682\tet al.\n2683\t,\n2684\t2021\n2685\t)\n2686\t.\n2687\tSilence intervals are extracted by applying a voice activity detector and deriving complementary non-speech regions.\n2688\tTo generate pseudofakes, the silence-duration sequence is stochastically compressed toward its mean, perturbed with controlled noise, truncated for overly long pauses, and constrained at sequence boundaries.\n2689\tThis reflects the tendency of synthetic speech to exhibit reduced variability and shorter silences, particularly at leading and trailing positions\n2690\t(Müller\n2691\tet al.\n2692\t,\n2693\t2021\n2694\t)\n2695\t.\n2696\tFeatures are summarized into\n2697\t10\n2698\t10\n2699\tproxies and classified using a dedicated MLP (10–32–16–1).\n2700\tThis expert is designed, trained, and calibrated independently from the others.\n2701\tIts calibration set differs slightly from those of the other experts, as real samples are drawn exclusively from ASVspoof 2019 due to the dataset-dependent nature of the targeted artifact.\n2702\tResults on ASVspoof 2019\n2703\tTTS\n2704\tattacks in\n2705\tTable\n2706\t4(b)\n2707\tshow expected traits of shortcut: particularly for Tacotron2 + WaveRNN, where previous experts were weak, the added expert provides very strong ‘evidence’ (\n2708\tLLR\n2709\t¿\n2710\t2\n2711\t2\n2712\t). At the ensemble level, the expert reduced the EER to around 12%. However, since the expert only relies on silence duration, the large magnitude of\n2713\tLLR\n2714\tand reduced EER suggest that the expert is exploiting the dataset-specific shortcut.\n2715\tWe show the new ensemble performance in\n2716\tFigure\n2717\t5\n2718\t, along with the confusion matrix at threshold\n2719\t0\n2720\t.\n2721\tFigure 5\n2722\t.\n2723\tEnsemble overall performance on ASVspoof 2019 after adding the sixth expert. ROC curve and confusion matrix (LLR scores threshold set at 0).\n2724\t6.\n2725\tConclusions\n2726\tWe proposed an interpretable speech deepfake detection framework based on artifact-specific expert models. The system decomposes detection into learning and recognition of predefined synthesis artifacts, each modeled by a dedicated classifier trained on pseudo-fake data.\n2727\tExpert outputs are calibrated into\n2728\tLLRs\n2729\t, providing a common interpretable measure of evidence linking decisions to artifact presence.\n2730\tExperiments show that (i) experts reliably detect their target artifacts, (ii) calibration is essential for meaningful comparison across experts, and (iii)\n2731\tLLR\n2732\tsummation is the most effective aggregation strategy.\n2733\tThe framework provides an interpretable mechanism for identifying synthesis artifacts while maintaining a modular architecture that can be extended as new artifact classes emerge. It also helps to diagnose potential dataset shortcuts.\n2734\tFuture work will focus on broadening the range of artifact-specific experts to capture the increasingly diverse characteristics of modern speech synthesis systems. Adapting automated rule-learning frameworks from the visual domain\n2735\t(Raza\n2736\tet al.\n2737\t,\n2738\t2024\n2739\t)\n2740\tto extract and compose speech anomalies into human-interpretable artifacts represents a promising direction for long-term, extendable development.\n2741\tOther topics, such as improved calibration and refined expert pipelines, are also expected to further boost the overall performance.\n2742\tOwing to its additive and modular design, these developments can be incorporated by introducing new experts while preserving the interpretability and extensibility of the overall framework.\n2743\tReferences\n2744\tD. Afchar, G. Meseguer-Brocal, K. Akesbi, and R. Hennequin (2025)\n2745\tA Fourier explanation of AI-music artifacts\n2746\t.\n2747\tIn\n2748\tProceedings of the International Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR)\n2749\t,\n2750\tCited by:\n2751\t§3.5\n2752\t.\n2753\tF. Alonso-Fernandez, K. B. Raja, R. Raghavendra, C. Busch, J. Bigun, R. Vera-Rodriguez, and J. Fierrez (2022)\n2754\tCross-sensor periocular biometrics in a global pandemic: Comparative benchmark and novel multialgorithmic approach\n2755\t.\n2756\tInformation Fusion\n2757\t83-84\n2758\t,\n2759\tpp. 110–130\n2760\t.\n2761\tCited by:\n2762\t§2.1\n2763\t.\n2764\tA. Bassit, F. Hahn, J. Peeters, T. Kevenaar, R. Veldhuis, and A. Peter (2021)\n2765\tFast and accurate likelihood ratio-based biometric verification secure against malicious adversaries\n2766\t.\n2767\tIEEE Transactions on Information Forensics and Security\n2768\t16\n2769\t,\n2770\tpp. 5045–5060\n2771\t.\n2772\tExternal Links:\n2773\tISSN 1556-6013, 1556-6021\n2774\tCited by:\n2775\t§2.1\n2776\t.\n2777\tI. Ben-Amor, J. Bonastre, B. O’Brien, and P. Bousquet (2023)\n2778\tDescribing the phonetics in the underlying speech attributes for deep and interpretable speaker recognition\n2779\t.\n2780\tIn\n2781\tProc. Interspeech 2023\n2782\t,\n2783\tpp. 3207–3211\n2784\t.\n2785\tCited by:\n2786\t§1\n2787\t,\n2788\tfootnote 1\n2789\t.\n2790\tT. Bořil, P. Šturm, R. Skarnitzl, and J. Volín (2017)\n2791\tEffect of formant and F0 discontinuity on perceived vowel duration: Impacts for concatenative speech synthesis\n2792\t.\n2793\tIn\n2794\tProc. Interspeech 2017\n2795\t,\n2796\tpp. 2998–3002\n2797\t.\n2798\tCited by:\n2799\t§3.1\n2800\t.\n2801\tC. Borrelli, P. Bestagini, F. Antonacci, A. Sarti, and S. Tubaro (2021)\n2802\tSynthetic speech detection through short-term and long-term prediction traces\n2803\t.\n2804\tEURASIP Journal on Information Security\n2805\t2021\n2806\t(\n2807\t1\n2808\t),\n2809\tpp. 2\n2810\t.\n2811\tCited by:\n2812\t§1\n2813\t.\n2814\tN. Brummer, A. Swart, and D. V. Leeuwen (2014)\n2815\tA comparison of linear and non-linear calibrations for speaker recognition\n2816\t.\n2817\tIn\n2818\tThe Speaker and Language Recognition Workshop (Odyssey 2014)\n2819\t,\n2820\tpp. 14–18\n2821\t.\n2822\tCited by:\n2823\t§2.3.2\n2824\t.\n2825\tC. Champod, A. Biedermann, J. Vuille, S. Willis, and J. De Kinder (2016)\n2826\tENFSI guideline for evaluative reporting in forensic science: a primer for 