erative adversarial networks for efficient and high fidelity speech synthesis\n.\nIn\nProc. NIPS\n,\nVol.\n33\n,\npp. 17022–17033\n.\nCited by:\n§3.3\n.\nC. L. Machado, X. Wang, and J. Yamagishi (2025)\nTowards a transparent and interpretable strategy for spoofed speech detection\n.\nIn\nThe 33rd Annual Conference of the International Association for Forensic Phonetics and Acoustics (IAFPA)\n,\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nM. Mandasari (2018)\nSpeaker recognition system in forensic conditions: The calibration and evaluation of the likelihood ratio\n.\nphd\n,\nRadboud University\n.\nCited by:\n§2.3.1\n.\nM. Mauch and S. Dixon (2014)\npYIN: A fundamental frequency estimator using probabilistic threshold distributions\n.\nIn\nIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP)\n,\npp. 659–663\n.\nCited by:\n§3.1\n.\nT. Merritt and S. King (2013)\nInvestigating the shortcomings of hmm synthesis\n.\nIn\nProceedings of 8th ISCA Speech Synthesis Workshop\n,\npp. 185–190\n.\nCited by:\n§3.2\n.\nJ. Mishra, M. Chhibber, H. Shim, and T. H. Kinnunen (2026)\nTowards explainable spoofed speech attribution and detection: a probabilistic approach for characterizing speech synthesizer components\n.\nComputer Speech & Language\n95\n,\npp. 101840\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n.\nM. Morise, F. Yokomori, and K. Ozawa (2016)\nWORLD: a vocoder-based high-quality speech synthesis system for real-time applications\n.\nIEICE Transactions on Information and Systems\n99\n(\n7\n),\npp. 1877–1884\n.\nCited by:\n§3.3\n.\nN. Müller, F. Dieckmann, P. Czempin, R. Canals, K. Böttinger, and J. Williams (2021)\nSpeech is silver, silence is golden: What do ASVspoof-trained models really learn?\n.\nIn\nProc. ASVspoof Challenge Workshop\n,\npp. 55–60\n.\nCited by:\n§4.1\n,\n§5.5\n.\nV. Negroni, L. Cuccovillo, P. Bestagini, P. Aichroth, and S. Tubaro (2026)\nMulti-task transformer for explainable speech deepfake detection via formant modeling\n.\nIn\nIEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Spee